# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charley-jones
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple started his major league career in 1878 with the National League's Milwaukee Grays, and that season, he had a career-high .354 batting average.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] He spent the next eight seasons with the Chicago White Stockings, for whom he starred as the leadoff hitter on five NL pennant winners.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] In 1880, Dalrymple led the league in hits (126) and runs scored (91).
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] In 1881, he became the first batter known to be given an intentional walk with the bases loaded.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] He hit four doubles in a game in 1883, which still ties him for the major league record.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] In 1884, aided by the short right field fence at his home park, Dalrymple hit a career-high 22 home runs and moved into sixth place on the all-time home run list.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] On the strength of 11 home runs for the 1885 champions, he moved up one place.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] For the remainder of his career, he hit only six home runs.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] His hitting declined in 1886, and his major league career ended five years later.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple died in Warren, Illinois at age 81.
[src:charley-jones/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple is sometimes cited as one of only three players in MLB history to win a batting title during his rookie season, a feat which he accomplished in 1878.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Adam Lynne Duvall was born on September 4, 1988, in Louisville, Kentucky, to parents Jeana and Alvin.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall was raised in Louisville, Kentucky, and played baseball at Butler High School.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In his junior high school season, he sustained a cracked vertebra.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] A subsequent surgery prevented him from playing during his senior year of high school.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall played college baseball at Western Kentucky University, Chipola College, and the University of Louisville.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall was drafted by the San Francisco Giants in the 11th round of the 2010 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He signed and made his professional debut that season for the Salem-Keizer Volcanoes.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 54 games, he batted .245 with four home runs and 18 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He spent 2011 with the Augusta GreenJackets where he slashed .285/.385/.527 with 22 home runs and 87 RBIs in 116 games.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 2012, he played for the San Jose Giants where he batted .258 and led all Class A players with 30 home runs along with 100 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall spent the 2013 season with the Richmond Flying Squirrels, tallying a .252 average, 17 home runs, and 58 RBIs over 105 games.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He was out of the lineup for part of April and May after sustaining an injury to his left thumb.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Following the season, Duvall was added to the 40-man roster on November 20, 2013.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He started the 2014 season with the Triple-A Fresno Grizzlies.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] The Giants promoted Duvall to the Major Leagues on June 25, 2014.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In his first MLB game, Duvall hit a home run off Cincinnati Reds pitcher Mike Leake.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He was sent back down to the Grizzlies on July 4 due to the return of Brandon Belt from the disabled list (DL).
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] When Belt was sent back to the DL due to lingering concussion symptoms, Duvall was called back up to the Giants to play first base, alongside Travis Ishikawa, Buster Posey, and Michael Morse.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On September 28, Duvall homered off San Diego Padres pitcher Tim Stauffer for his first career pinch-hit home run.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Over the course of 2014, Duvall played in 28 games with the Giants, finishing with a .192 batting average, three home runs, and five RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] The Giants earned a wild card spot with an 88–74 record and eventually won the 2014 World Series over the Kansas City Royals.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall, however, did not make any appearances in the postseason.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He began 2015 with the Sacramento River Cats.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On July 30, 2015, the Giants traded Duvall and Keury Mella to the Reds for Mike Leake; Leake being the pitcher Duvall hit his first major league home run off of.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Following the trade, Duvall joined the Louisville Bats.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On August 31, Duvall was recalled by the Reds to replace an injured Brennan Boesch.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] As a pinch-hitter, Duvall homered in his first at bat with the Reds.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Splitting time between Louisville and Cincinnati, Duvall played in 27 games with the Reds.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He posted a .219 batting average, five home runs, and nine RBIs for the Reds.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 2016, Duvall was included on the Reds' opening day roster.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] By June, he led the NL in slugging percentage and was tied for first in MLB in home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He was selected to the 2016 Major League Baseball All-Star Game as a reserve.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall was the first University of Louisville alumnus to become an MLB All-Star.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He also participated in the 2016 MLB Home Run Derby, losing to 2015 derby champion Todd Frazier in the semifinals.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In his first full season in the majors, Duvall played in 150 games and posted a .241 batting average, 33 home runs, and 103 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On April 18, 2017, Duvall hit his first career grand slam off of Kevin Gausman as the Reds won 9–3 over the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On July 14, with the bases loaded, Duvall hit his first career walk-off in the 11th inning off of T.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] McFarland of the Diamondbacks to give Cincinnati a 4–3 victory.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall finished 2017 with a .249/.301/.480 slash line to go along with 31 home runs and 99 runs batted in.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On May 9, 2018, Duvall hit his first career walk-off home run off A.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Ramos against the New York Mets to give the Reds a 2–1 victory.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On July 30, 2018, Duvall was traded to the Atlanta Braves in exchange for Lucas Sims, Matt Wisler, and Preston Tucker.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall struggled in 2018 with the Braves, batting .132 with no home runs or RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In both Atlanta and Cincinnati, Duvall batted just .195 with 15 homers and 61 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 2019, Duvall hit .267/.315/.567 with 10 home runs and 19 RBIs in 120 at bats in 41 games for Atlanta.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall and Marcell Ozuna became the first teammates in MLB history to hit three home runs in consecutive games, when Duvall did so against the Boston Red Sox on September 2, 2020.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Ozuna's equivalent feat the previous day was the first time a National League player had hit three home runs in a game at Fenway Park.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On September 9, Duvall hit three home runs in a game for the second time, while facing the Miami Marlins.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He became the first player in franchise history to have hit three home runs in a game twice.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He drove in nine runs, on a two-run home run followed by a three-run home run, then a grand slam.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In doing so, Duvall was the first player in MLB history to hit those home runs in such an order.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 2020 he batted .237/.301/.532 with 34 runs, 16 home runs (3rd in the NL), and 33 RBIs in 190 at bats, and was third in the NL in at bats per home run (11.9).
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On December 2, Duvall was nontendered by the Braves.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On February 9, 2021, Duvall signed a one-year, $2 million contract with the Miami Marlins.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On May 16 of the same year, he was responsible for securing the victory in the series finale facing the Dodgers, scoring three home runs for the team and hanging on with a score of 3–2.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall had 22 homers and 68 RBIs in 91 games with the team before the Atlanta Braves reacquired him.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On July 30, 2021, Duvall was traded to the Atlanta Braves in exchange for Alex Jackson.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Following the completion of a suspended game against the Braves and San Diego Padres on September 24, 2021, Duvall and Daniel Hudson became the first players in MLB history to play in two games for four different teams on the same day.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall and Hudson were members of the Miami Marlins and Washington Nationals, respectively, when the teams faced each other on July 21, 2021.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] The Braves–Padres game on that same day had been suspended, and by the time it resumed on September 24, 2021, Hudson had joined the Padres and Duvall the Braves.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In 2021, Duvall batted .228/.281/.491 with 38 home runs and 174 strikeouts and led the National League with 113 runs batted in.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He had the highest fly ball percentage in the major leagues, at 52.69%.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] In Game 5 of the 2021 World Series, he hit a two-out, first-inning grand slam on the first pitch from starting pitcher Framber Valdez, giving the Braves a 4–0 lead.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Despite his efforts, the Braves lost 9–5, sending the series to Game 6.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Nevertheless, the Braves won Game 6, giving the Braves their first title since 1995 and Duvall's first career World Series championship.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] At the end of the season, Duvall won the National League Gold Glove Award for right field.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] The Braves tendered Duvall a contract in December 2021.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] His salary for the 2022 season was decided by the arbitration process.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He asked for $10.275 million, but received the team's submitted offer $9.275 million when the arbitrator ruled in the Braves' favor.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] While pursuing a foul ball during a game against the Los Angeles Angels on July 23, Duvall tore the tendon sheath in his left wrist.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] The injury required surgery, which ended his season.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On January 24, 2023, Duvall signed a one-year contract with the Boston Red Sox, reportedly worth $7 million with an additional $3 million possible via potential bonuses.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall got off to a hot start in 2023, hitting three home runs (including a walk-off) and driving in 12 runs over his first seven games with the club, the latter of which was a Red Sox record.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He was recognized as AL Player of the Week for the first week of the season.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] However, this success was short lived, as he was placed on the injured list on April 10 due to a distal radius fracture of his left wrist suffered while trying to make a catch in the prior day's game.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On May 6, he was transferred to the 60-day injured list.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] For the week of August 21–27, Duvall was again recognized as AL Player of the Week, having hit 14-for-29 with five home runs and 12 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] He became a free agent following the season.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On March 14, 2024, Duvall signed a one-year, $3 million contract with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall was diagnosed with type 1 diabetes in 2012.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] They reside in both Nashville and Pinecrest, Florida.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] On June 20, 2023, he teamed up with Eli Lilly and Company and the American Diabetes Association to launch a nationwide campaign, "Tap the Cap" to increase awareness of insulin affordability solutions for all people living with diabetes.
[src:charley-jones/adam-duvall] Duvall has been an advocate for the importance of diabetes education.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré made his MLB debut with the Dodgers in 1998 at age 19.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He led the majors with 48 home runs with the Dodgers in 2004, was the team MVP of the Red Sox in 2010, played in the 2011 World Series for the Rangers, and tied for the major league lead in hits in 2013.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On September 19, 2014, Beltré surpassed Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time MLB leader for hits by a Dominican player, a record since broken by Albert Pujols in 2019.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 30, 2017, Beltré became the 31st player in MLB history to reach 3,000 hits and the first Dominican player to achieve that milestone.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré retired following the 2018 season with 3,166 career hits (most by a third baseman in MLB history), 477 home runs, and 1,707 runs batted in.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He hit for the cycle three times in his career, in 2008, 2012, and 2015, one of five players to do so in MLB history, the others being Bob Meusel, Babe Herman, Trea Turner, and Christian Yelich.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won the Gold Glove Award five times, Beltré is notable for his defensive prowess and career longevity as well as his power hitting.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He played in four MLB All-Star Games and won the Silver Slugger Award four times.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Upon his retirement, Beltré was the only third baseman in history with both 3,000 career hits and 400 home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] According to Baseball Reference, Beltré has the third-highest Wins Above Replacement among third basemen.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He retired as the all-time leader amongst third basemen in hits and RBIs, and ranked third in home runs amongst third basemen.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He is also the fifth major-leaguer to have hit at least 100 home runs for three different teams.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2024, Beltré was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in his first year of eligibility.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was born on April 7, 1979, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He attended Liceo Máximo Gómez High School.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] While working out at Campo Las Palmas in 1994, a Los Angeles Dodgers facility — one of the first of its kind for a Major League Baseball (MLB) team in the Dominican Republic — Beltré was spotted by scouts Ralph Avila and Pablo Peguero.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Though only 15 years old and weighing 130 lb (59 kg), Beltré featured a quick swing and live throwing arm.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On the insistence of Avila and Peguero, the Dodgers signed him in July 1994 with a $23,000 signing bonus.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was a highly touted prospect when he began his major league career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] After being called up to the majors from the then-Dodgers' Double-A affiliate San Antonio Missions, Beltré made his major league debut on June 24, 1998, starting at third base in the first game of an interleague series against the Anaheim Angels.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] At the time, he was the youngest player in the National League (NL).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] During his first at-bat, Beltré hit a two-out run batted in (RBI) double off Angels starter Chuck Finley into left field to score Paul Konerko from second base to tie the game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit his first home run six days later against Texas Rangers starter Rick Helling.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] At the end of the 1998 season, Beltré finished with 13 errors at third base while batting .215 with seven home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] At one point in the spring training prior to the start of the 1999 season, Beltré's agent, Scott Boras, commented to him that "he couldn't believe" his relatively rapid ascent to the majors and handling of "such a difficult position like third base" at age 20.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré replied that he was 19 years old, not 20.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Boras then realized that Beltré's date of birth in the Dodgers' records was incorrect and indicated the same to the team, but, that if they were to correct the mistake by compensating Beltré for signing him at younger than MLB's allowable age, they would no longer pursue the issue.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Team personnel at Las Palmas denied Boras' assertion.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] As a result, Boras and Beltré went public.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Boras convinced MLB commissioner Bud Selig to investigate the Dodgers, and MLB suspended their scouting operations in the Dominican Republic for one year, as well as Avila and Peguero.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Dodgers general manager Fred Claire, whom MLB did not contact during their investigation, publicly expressed surprise and that he was unaware of the incident.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Selig awarded Beltré $48,500 in damages.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2004, Beltré had a breakout season in which he established a number of career highs, including leading MLB with 48 home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Other career highs included batting .334, 200 hits, 121 RBI, 104 runs scored, .629 slugging percentage, and a then-career high 32 doubles.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He finished second in voting for the NL Most Valuable Player Award (MVP) and was honored with his first career Silver Slugger Award and the Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The Seattle Mariners signed Beltré as a free agent before the 2005 season to a five-year, $64 million deal.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Regressing to his pre-2004 form, he batted just .255 with 19 home runs and 87 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Manager Mike Hargrove said after the season that he thought Beltré was personally disappointed in his first season in Seattle.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] After Beltré batted .167 through April 10, Ted Miller of the *Seattle Post-Intelligencer* wrote that he might become one of the Mariners' greatest busts.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He hit his first home run on April 29, raising his average to .198, and continued to improve his performance, batting .281 with 24 home runs the rest of the season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 23, against the Boston Red Sox, Beltré hit an inside-the-park home run, the first one ever in Safeco Field history.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Though it was not a great season for Beltré, it was statistically his best as a Mariner.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He hit .276 and had 26 home runs, 99 RBI, and 41 doubles.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also won a Fielding Bible Award for being the top MLB defensive third baseman during the year.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Despite many miscues, Beltré received recognition for his defense in 2007.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He tied with Brandon Inge for the AL lead in errors by a third baseman, with 18, but ranked second in the league in assists, total chances, and range factor.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He had the lowest fielding percentage of all third basemen in the league at .958.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In spite of leading third basemen in errors, Beltré won his first Gold Glove Award, becoming the first Mariners third baseman to win the award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award, as well.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On September 1, Beltré hit for the cycle, becoming the fourth Mariner to do so.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Arizona Diamondbacks shortstop Stephen Drew hit for the cycle that day as well, the first time two players had done so since 1920.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré's decision not to wear a cup despite playing third base has been well-documented.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] This came back to hurt him on August 12, 2009, when he took a hard ground ball to the groin.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Although he stayed in for the remainder of the 14-inning victory, he was put on the 15-day disabled list (DL) after suffering bleeding in one of his testicles.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In his first game after returning from the DL, teammate Ken Griffey Jr. conspired with those responsible for the Safeco Field public address system to have Beltré's walk up music be the opening march from *The Nutcracker Suite*.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré declared free agency on November 5, 2009.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On January 7, 2010, Beltré signed a one-year, $9 million deal with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The contract had a $5 million player option for 2011 with a $1 million buyout.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] While Beltré's career before coming to the Red Sox had been regarded as somewhat disappointing, he hit .321 with 28 homers and 49 doubles in 2010, benefiting from the hitter-friendly Fenway Park.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Red Sox in batting average and tied David Ortiz for the team lead in RBIs (102).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Majors in doubles with 49 (also a career-high).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also finished fourth in the AL in batting average, and was fifth in the AL in total bases (326) and slugging percentage (.553).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also had two stolen bases on the year, and finished ninth in the MVP voting.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On January 5, 2011, Beltré signed a five-year, $80 million contract with the Texas Rangers.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He played with the Rangers for eight years until his retirement in 2018.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré's statistics improved when he was in his thirties.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] While he had previously played in pitcher-friendly ballparks in Los Angeles and Seattle, the Rangers' ballpark was known as a hitter-friendly environment.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] *The Wall Street Journal* described Beltré's Rangers tenure as "nothing short of brilliant".
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was on the 2011 American League All-Star team.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 22, Beltré strained his hamstring and was also placed on the DL.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On September 4, he singled to right for his 2,000th career hit.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On September 11, Beltré hit two home runs, including the 300th of his career, against the Oakland Athletics.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He was named the AL Player of the Month for September.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2011, Beltré batted .296 with 32 home runs, fifth in the AL.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He was third in the American League in slugging percentage (.561), sixth in RBIs (105), and ninth in OPS (.892).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The Fielding Bible said he saved 17 runs on defense in 2011.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On October 4, in Game 4 of the ALDS against the Tampa Bay Rays, Beltré became the sixth player to hit three home runs in a playoff game and the first do so in a Division Series.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in the World Series with the Rangers.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He added a fourth playoff home run in Game 5 of the World Series when he went down to one knee chasing an outside curve ball from Chris Carpenter.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Louis Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] More recognition was bestowed on Beltré for his defense.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On November 1, he was honored with his third Gold Glove Award and first by a Ranger third baseman since Buddy Bell's six-year run from 1979 to 1984.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also won his third Fielding Bible Award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On November 2, he was awarded the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was once again voted on to the All-Star Game starter, along with teammates Josh Hamilton and Mike Napoli.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] It was Beltré's third consecutive All-Star Game and the third of his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On August 22, against the Baltimore Orioles, Beltré hit three home runs in his first three at-bats, including two in the same inning.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He joined Pablo Sandoval, Albert Pujols, George Brett, Reggie Jackson, and Babe Ruth as the only players to hit a three-homer game in both the regular season and the postseason.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On August 24, he hit for the cycle for the second time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Both of his cycles came at Rangers Ballpark.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] With his first coming as a member of the Mariners, it was the first time in MLB history that a player had hit for the cycle more than once at the same stadium.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He joined Joe DiMaggio as the only players in big league history to have a three-homer game and a cycle in the same week.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] For his efforts, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for August 20–26.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] During the week, he hit .433 (13-for-30) with three doubles, one triple, five home runs, nine RBI, and seven runs scored.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He had the highest slugging percentage (1.100) in the majors, the most total bases (33), was tied for first in hits and home runs, and tied for second in RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] After the season, Beltré won more defensive accolades.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award and fourth overall.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He was won a Gold Glove Award and his second Platinum Glove Award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Wilson Sporting Goods honored him as one of their Defensive Players of the Year in the first year of that award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The Rangers organization named Beltré the team captain in 2013.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for July 1–7.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He batted .478 (11-for-23) with four home runs, two doubles and five RBI in six games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He led the American League in home runs, slugging (1.087), OPS (1.607), total bases (25), and extra-base hits (six) while producing the fourth-highest batting average.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit safely in all six games with two or more hits four times.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He had the 24th multi-homer game of his career with a pair of home runs on July 4 against Seattle.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Maintaining his strong hitting throughout July, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Month, his fourth career monthly award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He batted .369 with four doubles, nine homers, 19 RBI, and 13 runs scored over 26 games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He tied for the major league monthly lead in home runs with Alfonso Soriano and total bases with Torii Hunter (69).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré also was among the AL leaders in slugging percentage (second, .670), hits (tied for second, 38), extra-base hits (tied for fourth, 13), RBI (tied for fifth) and batting average (sixth).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He capped off the month with a walk-off home run to lead the Rangers past the Angels on July 31, the seventh walk-off home run of his career and first with Texas.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] It was his third monthly award with Texas, making him one of seven players to win multiple times with the Rangers, including Josh Hamilton (four), Rafael Palmeiro, Alex Rodriguez (both with three), Iván Rodríguez, Juan González and Rubén Sierra (two each).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] For the season, Beltré played in 161 games and totaled a .315 average, 30 homers, 92 RBI and .509 slugging percentage.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He led the AL with 199 hits and was fourth in batting average and fifth in total bases (321).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also made the top-10 in games played, slugging percentage and home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In the AL MVP voting, he was tied for seventh place.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The Dallas-Fort Worth chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America named Beltré the Texas Rangers Player of the Year.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On May 7, while facing Jorge de la Rosa of the Colorado Rockies, Beltré hit his 100th home run as a member of the Rangers, becoming the fifth player in major league history to hit 100 home runs with three teams, following Darrell Evans, Reggie Jackson, Alex Rodriguez, and Jim Thome.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On June 24, Beltré singled off Drew Smyly of the Detroit Tigers for his 2,500th career hit and the first hit of a 4-for-4 game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On September 18, Beltré singled off Sonny Gray in the first inning for his 2,591st hit, surpassing Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time hit leader among Dominican-born players.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré finished the 2014 season batting .324, his highest average since 2004, with 19 home runs and 77 RBI in 148 games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In February, the Rangers picked up Beltré's option, which would have become guaranteed if he had reached 586 plate appearances in the 2015 season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] While playing against Cleveland on May 15, Beltré hit his 400th home run on a sinker from Bruce Chen.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He became the 52nd player in MLB history to reach that plateau, and the fourth to do so while playing at least 75 percent of his games at third base.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On August 3, Beltré hit for the cycle with hits in each of the first, second, third, and fifth innings at home against the Houston Astros in a 12–9 win.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] It was his third career cycle, second as a Ranger, and third at the Rangers' home park, making him the only player ever to hit three cycles in one stadium.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He became the first Rangers player to hit for multiple cycles.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The first player in 82 years to hit for a third cycle, he became the fourth player to do so and tied the major league record for total career cycles, joining Long John Reilly, Bob Meusel, and Babe Herman.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] During the last week of the season, and the Rangers' run towards the AL West championship, Beltré batted .448 with two home runs and 13 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also went 2-for-4 with a home in the final game of the season to help the Rangers advance to their sixth AL West title.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He finished the season with 18 home runs, 83 RBI, 163 hits, and .287 average.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Enduring a torn ligament in his left thumb over the last three months of the season, Beltré had surgery to repair it immediately after the season ended.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The Phi Delta Theta fraternity presented Beltré with the 2014 Lou Gehrig Memorial Award on September 17, 2015, making him the first Rangers player to win the award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On April 15, Beltré and the Rangers agreed to a two-year, $36 million contract extension that would last through the 2018 seasons.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] The extension prevented Beltré from becoming a free agent at the end of the season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Displaying a drop to one knee, Beltré hit a home run on a curve ball from Jesse Hahn of Oakland on May 17.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In a May 29 game against the Pittsburgh Pirates, Beltré hit a two-run home run off Juan Nicasio to give him 1,501 career RBI, making him the 54th player to reach the milestone and the fourth third baseman.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 2, Beltré became the 28th player all time to amass 10,000 career at-bats.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 23, he became the 36th player all time to record 11,000 career plate appearances.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Two days later, he hit a walk-off home run, the ninth of his career, against the Athletics in the bottom of the ninth inning for a 7−6 win.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On August 24, Beltré, in a game against the Cincinnati Reds, hit a go-ahead two-out double for his 2,900th career hit and led the Rangers to a 6–5 win.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] With this hit, Beltré became the 39th player in major league history to reach the milestone.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré would once again show his signature home run knee drop after hitting a solo shot in the second inning in a game against the Houston Astros on September 13.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] His 30th of the season, it was the first time he reached the mark since 2013 and fifth in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Ten days later, his two-run home run in the eighth inning against the Athletics aided the Rangers in clinching the AL West division crown for the second year in a row and the seventh in franchise history.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also reached 100 RBI for the first time since 2012 and fifth time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He won the Gold Glove at third base, the fifth of his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré began the 2017 season on the 10-day disabled list after injuring his right leg near the end of spring training.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 4, Beltré hit his 600th career double, becoming the 17th player all-time to reach that milestone.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 7, Beltré became the 21st player to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On July 26, Beltré was ejected by umpire Gerry Davis; in a game against the Miami Marlins, Davis asked Beltré, who was the next scheduled batter, to move closer to the on-deck circle.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré responded by picking up the edge of the logo that marked the on-deck circle and moving it closer to where he had been standing, which prompted Davis to eject him.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré collected his 3,000th hit with a double into left field against Wade Miley of the Baltimore Orioles on July 30, making him the 31st player to reach this milestone and the first Dominican-born player to accomplish it.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in only 94 games in 2017 due to hamstring and calf problems.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Prior to the start of the 2018 season, the Rangers signed Bartolo Colón, giving them the only two active players with at least 20 seasons in the major leagues and the last two active players to have played in 1990s.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On April 5, Beltré doubled in the second inning versus the Oakland Athletics to pass Rod Carew as the all-time Latin American hits leader.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On June 13, Beltré hit a double that gave him 3,090 career hits; this made him the all-time leader in hits by a player not born in the United States, surpassing former Mariners teammate Ichiro Suzuki.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On November 20, 2018, Beltré announced his retirement.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2,933 games over 21 seasons, Beltré posted a .286 batting average with 3,166 hits, 477 home runs, 1,707 RBI, 121 stolen bases, 1,524 runs, 636 doubles, a .339 on-base percentage, a .480 slugging percentage, and a .960 fielding percentage.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 28 postseason games, he hit .261 with five home runs and 11 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré is regarded as one of the greatest third basemen of all time.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won five Gold Gloves, he was notable for his longevity, fielding ability, and power hitting.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré's signature home run swing included a drop to one knee when connecting with a breaking ball, particularly notable during Game 5 of the 2011 World Series against Cardinals ace Chris Carpenter.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré's defensive style was somewhat unorthodox.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Rangers manager Ron Washington remarked that Beltré fielded ground balls incorrectly by stopping before catching the ball and relying very little on the positioning of his feet in throwing the ball to first base.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré explained that his arm was so strong that early in his career he was making many throwing errors; by planting his feet, he was able to improve his accuracy despite his lack of proper foot positioning.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Another major league manager, Joe Maddon, compared the unique style of Beltré's defensive play to Ozzie Smith's "flair at shortstop", Stan Musial's "coiled batting stance", and the way Steve Carlton wrapped his left wrist before releasing a slider.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Commented Maddon further on Beltré's defense, "There's a lot of guys that did things unique to them that weren't out of the *Spalding Guide*.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He's a super smart player, knows where to position himself." Beltré was known for the sense of playfulness and joy that he exhibited on the field.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He had a routine with Rangers shortstop Elvis Andrus on pop flies where both men put their arms up to catch the ball.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] During a game against the Red Sox on June 26, 2016, Sandy León hit a foul ball which landed in the first row in the stands, just out of Beltré's reach.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] However, instead of returning immediately to the infield, he reached very close to the ball in a motion, pretending as if he were going to take it away from the fan who caught León's foul ball.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] As a hitter, Beltré also regularly pointed to the first base umpire to appeal a checked swing, a move usually only done by catchers.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré also had a joking relationship with Mariners pitcher Felix Hernández, which included Beltré getting ejected in 2010, when the two former teammates first faced each other, and Hernández hugging Beltré on the field in 2017, the day after Beltré's 3,000th major league hit.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was also known for his dislike of anyone touching the top of his head.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Before the game where he recorded his 3,000th hit, he let his teammates touch his head.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Much to his dismay, the act turned into a game, inducing repeat offenders, including Andrus.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] After a game in which he hit a grand slam that provided the decisive runs in a 5–2 win over the Athletics on August 15, 2016, he took a broom from the groundskeepers closet and began combing an area of infield dirt.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Still, Rougned Odor trotted to Beltré carrying a full drink bucket but missed drenching Beltré when he threw the blue sports drink at his teammate.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré played for the Dominican Republic in the 2006 World Baseball Classic (WBC).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He was named to the All-WBC team after hitting 4 home runs in six games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He also played in the 2017 WBC, batting 1-for-15 in four games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2017, he was dealing with leg injuries that caused him to miss the beginning of the MLB season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré was one of several Dominican Hall of Famers assisting general manager Nelson Cruz ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] On June 5, 2023, Beltré was named the honorary general manager for the Karachi Monarchs of the Baseball United league for their inaugural season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré served as the manager for the American League team in the 2024 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré has contributed to humanitarian activities in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex such as the Texas Rangers Baseball Foundation, Texas Rangers RBI program, the I Love Baseball program, which operates in the Dominican Republic, and the Baseball Tomorrow Fund.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] He has donated to Dave Valle's Esperanza International as well as foundations established by other major-league players, including Robinson Chirinos, Eddie Guardado, Joakim Soria, and Michael Young.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] In 2021, Beltré helped pay to reconstruct a baseball stadium in the Dominican Republic where he grew up playing.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-beltré] Beltré and his wife have three children.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was born in the United States, but was raised in Tijuana, Baja California, Mexico, until 1990, when he returned to the United States.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He played for Mexico in the 2006, 2009, 2013, and the 2017 editions of the World Baseball Classic and the 2020 Olympic Games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was the first overall pick in the 2000 MLB draft by the Florida Marlins.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was traded to the Rangers, and made his MLB debut with them in 2004.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was traded to the Padres after the 2005 season, where he was an All-Star selection three times and a two-time Gold Glove Award winner.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was traded to the Red Sox after the 2010 season, and was traded to the Dodgers in August 2012.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] After playing for the Dodgers throughout the 2017 season, he was traded to the Atlanta Braves, but was released without playing for them.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He then played for the Mets, who released him during the 2018 season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Adrián González was born in San Diego, California, to David and Alba González, both Mexican natives.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González is the youngest of three boys; his brothers are David Jr. and Edgar, a former big leaguer.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] After his birth, his parents moved the family to Tijuana, where his father owned an air-conditioner business.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] The three boys grew up playing baseball in Mexico, where their father had been a member of the Mexico national baseball team.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 1990, the family returned to the United States, settling in Bonita, California.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] While Adrián was drafted by the Florida Marlins out of high school, his brother Edgar Gonzalez attended San Diego State University and was selected by the Tampa Bay Rays in the 30th round of the 2000 draft.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Edgar debuted in the major leagues as a utility man with the San Diego Padres in 2008, joining his brother as a teammate.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 2012, David and Alba González were named George and Barbara Bush Little League Parents of the Year.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In November 2012, González was honored as one of 30 "exemplary citizens" by the mayor of Tijuana in an official ceremony.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was projected to be a late first-round pick out of Eastlake High School in Chula Vista, California; however, his stock increased with his senior-year performance.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In his senior year, he hit .645 with 13 home runs and 34 runs batted in.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In June 2000, González became the first infield position player to be drafted first overall since Alex Rodriguez in 1993.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was given a $3 million signing bonus by the Florida Marlins.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] While in the Marlins organization, González played with the Gulf Coast League Marlins, Kane County Cougars, Utica Blue Sox, Portland Sea Dogs (2002), Albuquerque Isotopes (2003), and Carolina Mudcats (2003).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] With the Single-A Kane County Cougars in his second professional season, González hit .312 with 17 home runs and 103 RBIs in 127 games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] As a result, he was selected by the Midwest League as its Most Valuable Player and Prospect of the Year.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He also played in the All-Star Futures Game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] After a wrist injury, the Marlins felt González would be hindered swinging the bat, so they included González in a June 2003 trade with the Texas Rangers, along with Ryan Snare and minor leaguer Will Smith, to acquire relief pitcher Ugueth Urbina to aid their championship drive.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González played with the Rangers' Class-AA team, the Frisco RoughRiders, until he made his major-league debut against the Seattle Mariners on April 18, 2004.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He recorded his first base hit on April 20 against Ramón Ortiz of the Anaheim Angels and his first home run on April 25 off Kevin Jarvis of the Seattle Mariners.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He played in 16 games for Texas in 2004 and in 43 games in 2005, with a combined batting average of .229 and 7 homers.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] After the season, González was traded to the San Diego Padres along with pitcher Chris Young and outfielder Terrmel Sledge.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In return, the Rangers received Adam Eaton and Akinori Otsuka.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Originally seen as an eventual replacement for Ryan Klesko at first base, González was given the job when Klesko underwent shoulder surgery.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] With extended playing time at first base in 2006, González continued to improve his hitting and defense.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On July 23, 2006, he was named the NL Player of the Week.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In his first full season, he led the Padres in batting average (.304) and home runs (24).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was the first player in Petco Park history to have more than one multiple home run game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On March 31, 2007, González agreed to a $9.5 million, four-year deal, with a club option for $5.5 million in 2011.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In the 2007 season, he led the Padres in home runs again, with 30, and had a team-high 100 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He led all Major League first basemen with 161 games and a career-high 46 doubles.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In the 2008 season, González finished with a .279 average and once again led the Padres with 36 home runs and 119 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was elected to the MLB All-Star Game as a reserve.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In the exhibition, he went 1 for 3 with a single and a sacrifice fly, driving in Miguel Tejada.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He won his first Gold Glove Award in 2008 at first base and set career highs in games played (162), home runs (36), RBI (119), runs scored (103), walks (74), and slugging percentage (.510).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was named the Padres MVP for the second time.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González played winter ball in the Mexican Pacific League with the Venados de Mazatlán.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In the Caribbean Series, he led his team past the Dominican Republic's Tigres del Licey with a record-setting 3 home runs on February 4.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On June 1, he was named the NL Co-Player of the Week for the second time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] During that week, González hit four home runs, tallied 10 RBIs, and had a 1.000 slugging percentage.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was elected to the MLB All-Star Game after voting by fellow players, managers and coaches.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He subsequently participated in that year's Home Run Derby, where he hit two home runs in the first round.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On August 1, González batted 6-for-6 with three RBI as the Padres topped the Milwaukee Brewers 13–6.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González's six hits are the most by any Padre in a nine-inning game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Three others have accomplished the feat, but did it in extra-inning contests.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He led the majors in walks in 2009 with 119 and set a major league record with eight consecutive multi-walk games, a record which still stands as of 2020.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He also hit 40 home runs for the first time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was named the Padres team MVP for 2009, his third time honored.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González started the 2010 season playing well.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On May 24, he was named the NL Player of the Week for the fourth time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On June 2, González hit a walk-off grand slam in the eleventh inning of a 5–1 victory over the New York Mets.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In July, González was elected to participate in his third consecutive All-Star game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] During the 2010 season, González had 176 hits in 591 at-bats, good for a .298 batting average, his highest since hitting .304 in 2006.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] His 93 walks put him in third place in the NL behind only Prince Fielder (114) and Albert Pujols (103).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He finished with 31 home runs and 101 RBI, the third time in his career he had 100 RBI or more.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González played in 160 games on the year, tying him with Rickie Weeks for 5th in the NL.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He scored 87 runs on the season, compiling 302 total bases, which also tied him with Weeks, for 6th in the NL.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was named team MVP for the third consecutive year and the fourth time overall with the Padres.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On December 6, 2010, González was traded to the Boston Red Sox for a package of right-handed pitcher Casey Kelly, first baseman Anthony Rizzo, outfielder Reymond Fuentes, and a player to be named later, later determined to be Eric Patterson.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On April 15, 2011, González and the Red Sox agreed to a seven-year contract extension worth $154 million through the 2018 season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On June 19, González hit his 1,000th career hit: a triple off of Milwaukee Brewers pitcher Yovani Gallardo.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On July 3, 2011, González was selected to the All-Star Game in Arizona along with teammates Josh Beckett, Jacoby Ellsbury, David Ortiz, Kevin Youkilis, and Jon Lester.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González hit a home run in the game and was responsible for the only run for the American League.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Additionally, Ortiz selected González as one of three sluggers to join him in the Home Run Derby, where he finished second to Robinson Canó.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González tied a record for most home runs in the final round of the home run derby at 11, which was then surpassed by the victor Canó.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González was named AL Player of the Month for June 2011 with a .404 average (40 for 99) – the best in the Majors for that month.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] After placing second in the 2011 Home Run Derby, González faced a home-run slump until he hit five home runs in ten at-bats on August 23–25.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On November 21, González finished seventh in MVP voting, trailing his teammate Ellsbury in second and the winner, Detroit Tigers ace Justin Verlander.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González appeared on the cover of baseball video game *MLB 12: The Show*.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 2012, González appeared in 123 games with the Red Sox, hitting .300 with 15 homers and 86 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On August 25, 2012, González was traded to the Los Angeles Dodgers (along with Josh Beckett, Nick Punto and Carl Crawford) and $11 million in cash for James Loney, Iván DeJesús Jr., Allen Webster and two players to be named later (Jerry Sands and Rubby De La Rosa).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In his first at bat with the Dodgers that same day, he hit a three-run home run against the Miami Marlins.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 36 games with the Dodgers, he hit .297 with 3 homers and 22 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In the 2013 season, González appeared in 157 games for the Dodgers and hit .293 with 22 home runs and 100 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was a candidate for the final vote at the All-Star Game but was not chosen for the game.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Louis Cardinals, González went 3 for 4 with 2 home runs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] The Dodgers would eventually lose the series in six games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González finished the 2014 season with 116 RBI, most in the majors.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was the Dodgers' nominee for the Hank Aaron Award, after hitting 27 home runs in 159 games.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] However, his batting average of .276 was the lowest of his career.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He finished up the season by winning the Silver Slugger Award for NL first baseman and also won several awards for his defense at first base, including the Gold Glove Award, Fielding Bible Award and Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González opened the 2015 season with five home runs in the first three games of the season, including three on April 8 against Andrew Cashner.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was the first MLB player to hit five home runs in the first three games of the season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] By homering in his fifth consecutive game, dating back to the end of the 2014 season, he tied the team record, which he shares with Roy Campanella (1950), Shawn Green (2001), Matt Kemp (2010), and Joc Pederson (2015).
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He won the player of the week award as a result of that performance.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was also awarded with the National League Player of the Month award for April as he hit .383 with eight home runs and 19 RBI in the month.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He recorded his 1,000th career RBI when he hit a two-run home run off Julio Teherán of the Atlanta Braves on May 26.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Gonzalez was selected to the All-Star Game, the first Dodger first baseman selected since Nomar Garciaparra in 2006.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He finished the season by hitting .275 in 156 games with 28 home runs and 90 RBI, the lowest RBI total he had since 2006.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González played for the Mexico national baseball team in the World Baseball Classic qualifiers during spring training in March 2016.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] The team was managed by his brother Edgar.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On June 22, 2016, during a game against the Washington Nationals, Gonzalez made a highlight-reel catch after a ball in foul territory deflected off Chase Utley's glove and off Gonzalez's leg.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On August 7, he hit his 300th career home run against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On the season he appeared in 156 games, with a .285 batting average, 18 homers and 90 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] It was the fewest home runs he had hit in a season since 2012.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On May 5, 2017, González was placed on the 10-day disabled list (DL) due to right elbow soreness.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] It was the first time in his MLB career that González was put on the DL.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González recorded his 2,000th career hit with a double off Johnny Barbato of the Pittsburgh Pirates on August 22.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González dealt with lingering back issues during the 2017 season, which caused him to spend half the season on the DL and lose playing time to rookie Cody Bellinger at first base.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] For the 2017 season, González only appeared in 71 games, batting .242/.287/.355 with 30 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was shut down for the season in September and did not appear on the Dodgers playoff roster.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In his final at-bat with the Dodgers, Gonzalez hit a home run against the Padres, giving him the rare distinction of having homered in both his first and last at-bats with the team.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On December 16, 2017, the Dodgers traded González, Charlie Culberson, Scott Kazmir, Brandon McCarthy, and $4.5 million to the Atlanta Braves for Matt Kemp.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] Immediately following the trade, the Braves designated González for assignment, then released him two days later.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González waived his no-trade clause to facilitate the trade, which he did because he wanted to test free agency.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On January 18, 2018, González signed a one-year contract with the New York Mets.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He was still due $21.5 million from his 2011 contract extension, with the Mets paying him $545,000 for the season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On June 10, 2018, the Mets granted González his unconditional release.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 54 games with the Mets, he batted .237/.299/.373; he had just three hits in his final 27 at bats with the team.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On March 30, 2021, González announced his return to baseball and officially signed with the Mariachis de Guadalajara of the Mexican League.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] On July 19, González announced that he would retire from professional baseball following the conclusion of the Mexican League season.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] In 43 games for Guadalajara, González batted .340/.412/.531 with 6 home runs and 41 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] He officially announced his retirement from professional baseball on February 5, 2022.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González and his wife Betsy reside in the San Diego County community of La Jolla.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] The couple created *The Adrián and Betsy González Foundation*, which is focused on empowering underprivileged youth in areas of athletics, education and health.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] As one of his charitable endeavors, González paid for the refurbishing of the baseball field in the Tijuana sports complex where he played as a youth.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González is a Christian and engraved on his bats is "PS 27:1" for verse 1 from Psalm 27.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] González has spoken about his faith saying, "I don't want to be remembered in baseball.
[src:charley-jones/adrián-gonzález] I want to be remembered as a good witness for Christ. ...
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] After 10 seasons with the Pirates, Oliver played for the Texas Rangers (1978–1981), Montreal Expos (1982–1983), San Francisco Giants (1984), Philadelphia Phillies (1984), Los Angeles Dodgers (1985), and Toronto Blue Jays (1985), over the course of his 18-year MLB career.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Nicknamed "**Scoop**", Oliver batted and threw left-handed.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was inducted into the Pittsburgh Pirates Hall of Fame in 2025.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver attended Portsmouth High School in Portsmouth, Ohio where he was teammates with future Major Leaguer Larry Hisle.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was a star basketball player and earned a scholarship to play college basketball for the Kent State Golden Flashes men's basketball team.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] However, before beginning college in 1964, he attended a tryout camp for the Philadelphia Phillies and one for the Pittsburgh Pirates in Salem, Virginia.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His father, who wanted him to attend college, allowed him to sign with the Pirates at 17 years old for $5,000.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was promoted to the Major Leagues on September 14, 1968, the day his father, Al Oliver Sr., died.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In his official rookie season, Oliver batted .285 with 17 home runs and drove in 70 runs, placing second in the 1969 National League Rookie of the Year voting.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The following season, 1970, Oliver hit .270 and was fifth in the NL with seven sacrifice flies.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also finished second in the league with the 14 times he was hit by a pitch (the previous year he was plunked 12 times, fourth in the league).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates won the National League East title for their first trip to the postseason since winning the 1960 World Series.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] However, they lost to the Cincinnati Reds in the 1970 National League Championship Series.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] On September 1, 1971, the Pirates fielded what is believed to be the first all-black lineup in the history of the league.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver played first base, joining second baseman Rennie Stennett, center fielder Gene Clines, right fielder Roberto Clemente, left fielder Willie Stargell, catcher Manny Sanguillén, third baseman Dave Cash, shortstop Jackie Hernández and pitcher Dock Ellis in the starting lineup.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver ended the season with a .282 average, including 31 doubles (8th in the NL), seven triples (10th), 10 sacrifice flies (2nd), and five hit-by-pitches (good for 9th in the league).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] After beating the San Francisco Giants in the 1971 National League Championship Series, the Pirates won the World Series, beating the Baltimore Orioles in seven games with Oliver as their regular center fielder.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1972, Oliver raised his batting average to .312, good for sixth in the league.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He hit 12 home runs with 89 RBI (10th in the NL).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He scored 88 runs (8th in the league) and totalled 176 hits, which was also 8th in the NL.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was named to his first All-Star game while finishing seventh in the NL MVP voting.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1973, Oliver hit 20 home runs and drove in 99 runs (7th in the NL) while batting .292.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates won their third consecutive NL East title, however, they lost to the Reds 3 games to 2 in the NLCS.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates offense led the National League in batting average with a .274 average and led the NL with 1505 hits.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1974, Oliver hit .321 with 198 hits, which were second and fourth in the National League respectively.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also hit 38 doubles and 12 triples, which were both second best in the NL.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was seventh in NL MVP voting for the second time in three years.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] About Oliver, Willie Stargell said, "When it came to hitting ... all he ever did was crush the ball.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Al was the perfect number three hitter because you knew he was going to make contact".
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He had a 23-game hitting streak in 1974 and another streak of 21 games where he got at least one hit.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates won the NL East but lost to the Dodgers 3 games to 1 in the NLCS.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates offense, known as the "Pittsburgh Lumber Company" again led the NL in hitting with 1560 hits and a .274 team batting average.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver's 90 runs in 1975 was tenth in the NL as he hit .280 with 18 home runs and 84 RBI and played in the All-Star game for the second time.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He tied a personal mark with 65 extra base hits, which was good for 5th in the NL, 39 of which were doubles, which put him third in the NL in that category.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was named as an outfielder on The Sporting News 1975 NL All-Star Team.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates won the NL East again, but were swept by the Cincinnati Reds 3 games to none in the NLCS.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1976 Oliver hit .323; this was his first of nine straight .300+ seasons.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He played in the All-Star game once again, batting .360 at the break, but an inner ear infection sidelined him in the second half, and prevented him from finishing in the top 10 in batting categories.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was voted the National League Player of the Month for June.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1977, as part of the so-called "Pittsburgh Lumber Company", Oliver hit .308 (tenth in the NL) with 19 home runs and 82 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also stole a career-high 13 bases, although he was thrown out 16 times along the way.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His 8 sacrifice flies were fifth in the league as well.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was traded along with Nelson Norman from the Pirates to the Rangers in the first four-team blockbuster deal in Major League Baseball history on December 8, 1977, that also involved the Atlanta Braves, New York Mets and a total of eleven players changing teams.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Rangers also received Jon Matlack from the Mets.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Pirates acquired Bert Blyleven from the Rangers and John Milner from the Mets.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Going to the Braves from the Rangers were Adrian Devine, Tommy Boggs and Eddie Miller.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The Mets got from the Braves Willie Montañez and from the Rangers Tom Grieve and Ken Henderson who was sent to New York to complete the transaction three months later on March 15, 1978.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1978 Oliver was second in the AL with a .324 batting average, and his 170 hits were good for eighth in the league, and his 35 doubles were sixth in the league.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The next season, 1979, Oliver hit .323, good for fifth in the league (the fifth time he had finished among his league's top ten in batting).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was voted to the AL All-Star team for the first time.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was the outfielder on The Sporting News 1980 AL Silver Slugger Team.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] On August 17 at Tiger Stadium, he established an American League record with 21 total bases in a doubleheader (four home runs, a double and a triple).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] On May 23, 1979, and August 17, 1980, Oliver hit 3 home runs in each game, the first against the Minnesota Twins in a 7–2 win and a year later against the Detroit Tigers in the second game of a doubleheader in a 12–6 victory.(He added another in the 1st game, to make it 4 in the double header.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1981 Oliver was ninth in the AL with a .309 average, sixth in hits with 130, and second in doubles with 29, while playing in the All-Star game (his fifth).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also won his second consecutive Silver Slugger Award as the best hitter at his position, which in 1981 was designated hitter.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He became the first player to win Silver Slugger Awards at two different positions.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also became the Rangers' all-time leading hitter (.319) and reached the club's top ten in virtually every offensive category.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver wanted an extension to his contract of which he was paid $320,000 annually and had four years remaining, but asked to be traded after Rangers management rejected his renegotiation request.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was set to be dealt to the New York Yankees for Oscar Gamble, Bob Watson and Mike Morgan prior to the 1982 regular season.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Gamble's contract listed eight teams to which he could be traded, not including the Rangers, so the deal was squashed.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was sent to the Montreal Expos for Larry Parrish and Dave Hostetler on March 31, 1982, instead.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He became the Expos' starting first baseman.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1982 with the Expos, Oliver hit a career-high .331 batting average to win the National League batting crown.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also led the NL in hits (204), doubles (43), extra bases (67), and total bases (317), and tied with Dale Murphy for the RBI lead with 109.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His 43 doubles tied his 1980 career-high, and his 67 extra base hits was also a career-high as well as his 22 home runs, breaking his 1973 personal best.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In addition to playing in his sixth All-Star game, he was third in the NL MVP voting and won his third consecutive Silver Slugger Award, this time as a first baseman.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was also the first baseman on The Sporting News' NL All-Star Team.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was voted the Montreal Expos Player of the Year at the end of the season.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In 1983 Oliver led the NL in doubles with 38 and was fourth in the NL in hits with 184.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He hit .300 once again and topped the 2500 career hit level (August 10, 1983, off Mets' pitcher Carlos Diaz). and Oliver was selected for his seventh All-Star game, starting at first base in the 1983 Classic.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] On February 27, 1984, Oliver was traded to the San Francisco Giants for Fred Breining and Max Venable.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] The San Francisco Giants later sent Andy McGaffigan to the Montreal Expos to complete the trade.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Later that same year, on August 20, 1984, he was again traded, this time with Renie Martin to the Philadelphia Phillies for Kelly Downs and George Riley.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In the 1985 offseason, Oliver was traded by the Phillies to the Los Angeles Dodgers for Pat Zachry.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Then, on July 9, 1985, he was traded by the Los Angeles Dodgers to the Toronto Blue Jays for Len Matuszek.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] With the Blue Jays, Oliver delivered two game-winning hits in the first four games of the 1985 American League Championship Series against Kansas City.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] However, the Royals rallied to win the last three games.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In the seventh and deciding game, the lefty Oliver started as the DH against right-hander Bret Saberhagen.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] But after pitching three scoreless innings, Saberhagen departed the game due to injury.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Lefty Charlie Leibrandt was inserted, thus giving the Royals the platoon advantage.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Right-handed batter Cliff Johnson pinch hit for Oliver, and struck out, ending a Blue Jays rally.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver was caught by TV cameras angrily scowling in the dugout, knowing his night—and as it turned out, his season and career—were over.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He is one of the few players to play for both major league Canadian teams, the Toronto Blue Jays and the Montreal Expos.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver claims that he was forced to retire due to collusion.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Courts ruled that there was collusion among baseball owners in the mid-1980s, which included Oliver (and nine others) when a judge ruled that he was entitled to $680,031.05 in 1995.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Several players, including Kirk Gibson, were allowed to file for free agency a second time because of the court order based on the "collusion" finding.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver himself believes that he could have played four or five more years.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Andre Dawson said, "Al, as a lifetime .300 hitter after 18 seasons, I feel is deserving of induction into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] There is no question in my mind had he not been forced out of the game by collusion, had he been given an all-out honest attempt to achieve 3,000 hits, he would have done it.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was pushed out of the game when he was still a .300 hitter.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver batted .300 or more eleven times.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His 2,743 career hits rank 58th on the all-time list.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In the time of his career, he was third in hits among all players, behind Pete Rose and Rod Carew.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also ranks among all-time top 50 in games played (2368), total bases (4083), RBI (1326) and extra-base hits (825).
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He was among the league's top ten in doubles nine times and among the league's top ten in hits nine times as well and finished in the top ten in batting average nine times.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Five times he was among the league's top ten in total bases and four times he was in the top ten in RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Because of these feats, his name has been mentioned more than once as a possible inductee into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver hit the last home run at Forbes Field.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His shot came off Milt Pappas in the sixth inning of the last game played at the stadium, the second game of a June 28, 1970, doubleheader against the Chicago Cubs.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] He also drove in the first run ever scored at Three Rivers Stadium.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His first-inning double off Gary Nolan drove in Richie Hebner in that stadium's inaugural game, on July 16 of that same 1970 season.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] However, the Cincinnati Reds defeated the Pirates 3–2 .
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] His son, Aaron Oliver, played football for the Texas A&M University team that won the 1998 Big 12 Conference Championship.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Aaron, a four-year letterman and three-year starter, caught the first touchdown pass in Big 12 history.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] On April 22, 2013, the Portsmouth City Council unanimously passed a resolution recognizing and appointing Al Oliver as "Mr.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Ambassador" for the City of Portsmouth in recognition of his various efforts on behalf of the community and southern Ohio.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] Oliver is portrayed on one of the Floodwall Murals in Portsmouth, Ohio, honoring local Major League Baseball players, scouts, and umpires.
[src:charley-jones/al-oliver] In September 2014, Oliver released his second book, titled *Life is a Hit, Don't Strike Out* that chronicled his life and career.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County comprises the Burlington, NC Metropolitan Statistical Area, which is also included in the Greensboro–Winston-Salem–High Point, NC Combined Statistical Area, which had an estimated population of 1,736,099 in 2023.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Before being formed as a county, the region had at least one known small Southeastern tribe of Native Americans in the 18th century, the Sissipahaw, who lived in the area bounded by modern Saxapahaw, the area known as the Hawfields, and the Haw River.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] European settlers entered the region in the late 17th century chiefly following Native American trading paths, and set up their farms in what they called the "Haw Old Fields," fertile ground previously tilled by the Sissipahaw.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The paths later became the basis of the railroad and interstate highway routes.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County was named after Great Alamance Creek, site of the Battle of Alamance (May 16, 1771), a pre-Revolutionary War battle in which militia under the command of Governor William Tryon crushed the Regulator movement.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Great Alamance Creek, and in turn Little Alamance Creek, according to legend, were named after a local Native American word to describe the blue mud found at the bottom of the creeks.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Other legends say the name came from another local Native American word meaning "noisy river," or for the Alamanni region of Rhineland, Germany, where many of the early settlers came from.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] During the American Revolution, several small battles and skirmishes occurred in the area that became Alamance County, several of them during the lead-up to the Battle of Guilford Court House, including Pyle's Massacre, the Battle of Lindley's Mill, and the Battle of Clapp's Mill.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In the 1780s, the Occaneechi Native Americans returned to North Carolina from Virginia, this time settling in what is now Alamance County rather than their first location near Hillsborough.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In 2002, the modern Occaneechi tribe bought 25 acres (100,000 m2) of their ancestral land in Alamance County and began a Homeland Preservation Project that includes a village reconstructed as it would have been in 1701 and a 1930s farming village.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] During the early 19th century, the textile industry grew heavily in the area, so the need for better transportation grew.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] By the 1840s, several mills were set up along the Haw River and near Great Alamance Creek and other major tributaries of the Haw.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Between 1832 and 1880, at least 14 major mills were powered by these rivers and streams.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Mills were built by the Trollinger, Holt, Newlin, Swepson, and Rosenthal families, among others.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] One of them, built in 1832 by Ben Trollinger, is still in operation.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] It is owned by Copland Industries, sits in the unincorporated community of Carolina and is the oldest continuously operating mill in North Carolina.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] One notable textile produced in the area was the "Alamance plaids" or "Glencoe plaids" used in everything from clothing to tablecloths.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Alamance Plaids manufactured by textile pioneer Edwin M.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Holt were the first colored cotton goods produced on power looms in the South, and paved the way for the region's textile boom.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] (Holt's home is now the Alamance County Historical Society.) But by the late 20th century, most of the plants and mills had gone out of business, including the mills operated by Burlington Industries, a company based in Burlington.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] By the 1840s, the textile industry was booming, and the railroad was being built through the area as a convenient link between Raleigh and Greensboro.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Efforts to split a new county off from Orange County began in 1842.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] A bill to form the county from Orange County was filed by Giles Mebane on January 1, 1849 and passed the legislature later that month.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] An election was held on April 19, 1849 and the split was approved by the voters, with the new county being established officially on April 24 by Governor Charles Manly.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In March 1861, Alamance County residents voted overwhelmingly against North Carolina's secession from the Union, 1,114 to 254.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Two delegates were sent to the State Secession Convention, Thomas Ruffin and Giles Mebane, who both opposed secession, as did most of the delegates sent to the convention.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] At the time of the convention, around 30% of Alamance County's population were slaves (total population around 12,000, including roughly 3,500 slaves and 500 free Black people).
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] North Carolina was reluctant to join other Southern states in secession until the Battle of Fort Sumter in April 1861.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] When Lincoln called up troops, Governor John Ellis replied, "I can be no party to this wicked violation of the laws of the country and to this war upon the liberties of a free people.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] You can get no troops from North Carolina." After a special legislative session, North Carolina's legislature unanimously voted for secession on May 20, 1861.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] No battles took place in Alamance County, but it sent its share of soldiers to the front lines.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In July 1861, for the first time in American history, soldiers were sent in to combat by rail.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The 6th North Carolina was loaded onto railroad cars at Company Shops and transferred to the battlefront at Manassas, Virginia (First Battle of Manassas).
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Although the citizens of Alamance County were not directly affected throughout much of the war, in April 1865, they witnessed firsthand their sons and fathers marching through the county just days before the war ended with the surrender at Bennett Place near Durham.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Johnston stopped to say farewell to his soldiers for the last time.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] By the end of the war, 236 people from Alamance County had been killed in the course of the war, more than any other war since the county's founding.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Some of the Civil War's most significant effects were seen after it ended.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County briefly became a center of national attention when in 1870 Wyatt Outlaw, an African-American town commissioner in Graham, was lynched by the Ku Klux Klan.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] He was president of the Alamance County Union League of America (a progressive reform branch of the Federal Government), helped to establish the Republican party in North Carolina, and advocated establishing a school for African Americans.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] His offense was that Governor William Holden had appointed him a justice of the peace, and he had accepted the appointment.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Outlaw's body was found hanging 30 yards from the courthouse, with a note pinned to his chest reading, "Beware!
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] You guilty parties – both white and black." Outlaw was the central figure in political cooperation between blacks and whites in the county.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] On July 8, 1870, Governor Holden declared Caswell County to be in a state of insurrection and sent North Carolina militiamen to Caswell and Alamance Counties, under the command of Union veteran George W.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Kirk, beginning the so-called Kirk–Holden war.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Kirk's troops ultimately arrested 82 men.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Grand Jury of Alamance County indicted 63 klansmen for felonies and 18 for the murder of Wyatt Outlaw.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Soon after the indictments were brought, Democrats in the legislature passed a bill to repeal the law under which the indictments had been secured.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Democratic Party then used a national program of "Amnesty and Pardon" to proclaim amnesty for all who committed crimes on behalf of a secret society.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] This was extended to the klansmen of Alamance County.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] There would be no justice in the case of Wyatt Outlaw.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Holden's support for Reconstruction led to his impeachment and removal by the North Carolina Legislature in 1871.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The county was once the state leader in dairy production.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Several dairies including Melville Dairy in Burlington were headquartered in the county.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] With increasing real estate prices and a slump in milk prices, most dairy farms have been sold and many of them developed for real estate purposes.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] During World War II, Fairchild Aircraft built airplanes at a plant on the eastern side of Burlington.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Among the planes built there was the AT-21 gunner, used to train bomber pilots.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Near the Fairchild plant was the Western Electric Burlington works.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] During the Cold War, the plant built radar equipment and guidance systems for missiles and many other electronics for the government, including the guidance system for the Titan missile.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The plant closed in 1992 and sat abandoned until 2005, when it was purchased by a local businessman for manufacturing.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The USS *Alamance*, a *Tolland*-class attack cargo ship, was built during and served in and after World War II.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County's population has grown significantly, with the city of Mebane tripling in size between 1990 and 2020.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Some growth has been attributed to illegal immigration, which has led to ongoing legal issues.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In 2012, the Department of Justice found the Alamance County Sheriff's Office to use discriminatory policing, however the case was dismissed by U.S.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Schroeder, finding that the government failed to demonstrate that the ACSO had engaged in discriminatory policing.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Beginning in 2014, the county has been home to a number of political demonstrations.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In October 2020, during a demonstration prior to the 2020 United States presidential election, Alamance County sheriff's deputies and Graham police used pepper spray against crowd members.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Law enforcement reported that pepper spray had been deployed to disperse the crowd following an assault on an officer who was trying to shut down a generator the march organizers had brought, in violation of a signed agreement.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The county is in the Piedmont physiographical region.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] It has a general rolling terrain with the Cane Creek Mountains rising to over 970 ft (300 m) in the south-central part of the county just north of Snow Camp.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Bass Mountain, one of the prominent hills in the range, is home to a world-renowned bluegrass music festival every year.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Also, isolated monadnocks are in the northern part of the county that rise to near or over 900 ft (270 m) above sea level.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The largest river that flows through Alamance County is the Haw, which feeds into Jordan Lake in Chatham County, eventually leading to the Cape Fear River.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The county is also home to numerous creeks, streams, and ponds, including Great Alamance Creek, where a portion of the Battle of Alamance was fought.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The three large municipal reservoirs are: Lake Cammack, Lake Mackintosh, and Graham-Mebane Lake (formerly Quaker Lake).
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The southwest end of the county is drained by North Rocky River Prong and Greenbrier Creek, two tributaries of the Rocky River in the Deep River system.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] As of the 2020 census, there were 171,415 people, 67,925 households, and 41,793 families residing in the county.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] 21.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 17.4% were 65 years of age or older; for every 100 females there were 90.1 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 86.5 males.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 61.7% White, 19.8% Black or African American, 0.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 1.7% Asian, 0.1% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 9.0% from some other race, and 6.8% from two or more races.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 14.4% of the population.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] 73.6% of residents lived in urban areas, while 26.4% lived in rural areas.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] There were 67,925 households in the county, of which 30.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Of all households, 44.1% were married-couple households, 17.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.6% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] About 29.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] There were 73,385 housing units, of which 7.4% were vacant.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Among occupied housing units, 64.9% were owner-occupied and 35.1% were renter-occupied.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.9%.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 151,131 people, 59,960 households, and 39,848 families residing in the county.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The population density was 347.4 people per square mile (134.1 people/km2).
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] There were 66,055 housing units at an average density of 151.9 units per square mile (58.6 units/km2).
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 71.1% White, 18.8% Black or African American, 0.7% Native American, 1.2% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 6.1% from other races, and 2.1% from two or more races.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] 11% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] There were 59,960 households, out of which 29.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.2% were married couples living together, 14.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.5% were non-families.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] 27.8% of all households were made up of individuals, and 26.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 2.98.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In the county, the population was spread out, with 26.7% under the age of 19, 7.2% from 20 to 24, 25.1% from 25 to 44, 26.3% from 45 to 64, and 14.5% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] For every 100 females there were 92.50 males.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.00 males.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $44,430, and the median income for a family was $54,605.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Males had a median income of $31,906 versus $23,367 for females.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $23,477.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] About 13.7% of families and 16.1% of the population were below the poverty line, including 25% of those under age 18 and 8.7% of those age 65 or over.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The last Democratic nominee for president to carry Alamance County was Jimmy Carter in 1976.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Despite this, Democrat Josh Stein won the county in the 2024 North Carolina gubernatorial election.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Democratic presidential nominee Kamala Harris also won 45.2% of the vote in the county, the highest percentage since 1976.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County is a member of the regional Piedmont Triad Council of Governments.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The county is led by the Alamance County Board of Commissioners and the County Manager, who is appointed by the Board of Commissioners.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] County residents also elect two other county government offices: the Sheriff and Register of Deeds.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County has provided North Carolina with three governors and two U.S. senators: Governor Thomas Holt, Governor and Senator Kerr Scott, Governor Robert W.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] (Bob) Scott (Kerr Scott's son), and Senator B.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County adopted the council-manager form of government in the 1970s, where the day-to-day management of county business is done by an individual hired by the commissioners' board.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Walker and David Smith held dual roles as county manager and county attorney during their terms.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Terry Johnson has served as sheriff since 2002.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] In 2016, he settled a lawsuit from the Department of Justice that alleged bias in policing, with federal investigators finding that the sheriff’s office targeted Latino neighborhoods for traffic enforcement and that Latino drivers in the county were four to 10 times more likely to be stopped.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Paramount Theater serves as a center of dramatic presentations in the community.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] To the south there is the Snow Camp Outdoor Drama which has plays from late spring to early fall in the evenings.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County is also home to the Haw River Ballroom, a large music and arts venue in Saxapahaw.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County, Burlington, Graham, Elon, Haw River, Swepsonville, and Mebane all have small parks that are not listed here.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Burlington Sock Puppets, members of the Appalachian League, a wood-bat collegiate summer league, play their home games at Burlington Athletic Stadium in Fairchild Park.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] They were previously known as the Burlington Royals from 2007 to 2020.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Royals were rebranded as the Sock Puppets following the contraction and reorganization of minor league baseball prior to the 2021 season.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] 2021 was the inaugural season for the revamped Appalachian League and the Sock Puppets.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Prior to being known as the Royals, the team was also known as the Burlington Indians from 1986 to 2006.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] This version of the team has been active since 1985, but Burlington hosted a minor league baseball team for many years under the Burlington Indians and Burlington Bees.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Elon University Phoenix play in the town of Elon.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The Phoenix compete in the NCAA's Division I (Championship Subdivision in football) Colonial Athletic Association.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Intercollegiate sports include baseball, basketball, cross-country, football, golf, soccer, and tennis for men, and basketball, cross-country, golf, indoor track, outdoor track, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball for women.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Today, Alamance County is often described as a "bedroom" community, with many residents living in the county and working elsewhere due to low tax rates, although the county is still a major player in the textile and manufacturing industries.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The current county-wide tax rate for Alamance County residents is 58.0 cents per $100 valuation.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] This does not include tax rates imposed by municipalities or fire districts.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Alamance County is served by the Alamance-Burlington School System, several private elementary and secondary schools, Alamance Community College, and Elon University.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The county is divided into thirteen townships, which are both numbered and named.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] According to a 1975 study of the history of post offices in North Carolina by Treasure Index, Alamance County has 27 ghost towns that existed in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] Additionally, five other post offices no longer exist.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] These towns and their post offices were either abandoned as organized settlements or absorbed into the larger communities that now make up Alamance County.
[src:charley-jones/alamance-county-north-carolina] The population ranking of the following table is based on the 2020 census of Alamance County.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was a highly regarded hitter who possessed a "combination of contact hitting ability, patience and raw power." He was the National League (NL) Most Valuable Player (MVP) in 2005, 2008, and 2009 and is an 11-time All-Star (2001, 2003–2010, 2015, 2022).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was a six-time Silver Slugger and won two Gold Glove awards at first base in his career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols twice led the NL in home runs and once each in batting average, doubles, and runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols surpassed 3,000 career hits, becoming the 32nd MLB player to reach that milestone.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] During his final season, Pujols moved into second place all-time for career RBIs and total bases and became the fourth player with 700 career home runs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was born and raised in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, mostly by his grandmother, America Pujols, and 10 of his uncles and aunts.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His father, Bienvenido Pujols, was a softball pitcher who struggled with alcoholism.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols often had to take his father home when he got drunk following games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Growing up, Pujols practiced baseball using limes for balls and a milk carton for a glove.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols, his father, and his grandmother immigrated in 1996 to Washington Heights in New York City, where Pujols witnessed a shooting at a bodega.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Partly because of the shooting, they moved two months later to Independence, Missouri, to join some relatives.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols played baseball at Fort Osage High School in Independence and was named an All-State athlete twice.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] As a senior, he was walked 55 times intentionally, but he still hit eight home runs in 33 at-bats.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] One of his home runs travelled 450 feet (140 m).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After graduating from high school a semester early in December 1998, he was given a baseball scholarship to Maple Woods Community College.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit a grand slam and turned an unassisted triple play in the first game of his only college season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Playing shortstop, he batted .461 with 22 home runs as a freshman before deciding to enter the Major League Baseball (MLB) draft.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Few teams were interested in Pujols because of uncertainty about his age, which position he would play, and his build.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Tampa Bay Rays scout Fernando Arango recommended that his team sign Pujols, and quit his job when Tampa Bay failed to do so.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was not drafted until the 13th round of the 1999 Major League Baseball (MLB) draft, when the St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Louis Cardinals selected him with the 402nd overall pick.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols initially turned down a $10,000 bonus and spent the summer playing for the Hays Larks of the Jayhawk Collegiate League (a summer league in the National Baseball Congress).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] When the Cardinals increased their bonus offer to $60,000, he signed.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began his minor league career in 2000 playing third base with the Peoria Chiefs of the single-A Midwest League.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .324 with 128 hits, 32 doubles, six triples, 17 home runs and 84 RBI, in 109 games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was voted the league's Most Valuable Player and named to the All-Star team.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols also played 21 games with the Potomac Cannons in the high-A Carolina League that year, batting .284 with 23 hits, nine doubles, one triple, two home runs and 10 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished the 2000 season with the Memphis Redbirds in the AAA Pacific Coast League (PCL), and after appearing in three regular season games with them, he batted .367 in the playoffs and was named the postseason Most Valuable Player (MVP) as the Redbirds won their first PCL title.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] According to La Russa, he and the rest of Cardinals management were impressed enough by Pujols that they decided to promote him to the big league club even before Bonilla's injury.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Cardinals executive John Vuch backed this up, calling the link between Pujols and Bonilla an "old wives' tale" and stating that the competition for the last roster spot was actually between Bonilla and John Mabry.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Although the team did not require Pujols to fill any particular position, the Cardinals activated him to the Opening Day roster, and he started all season at third base, right field, left field, or first base.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On Opening Day against the Colorado Rockies on April 2, Pujols became the first major league player born in the 1980s.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In that game, he recorded his first career hit, a single against pitcher Mike Hampton in an 8–0 loss.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Four days later, he had three hits and three RBI — including his first home run — against the Arizona Diamondbacks' Armando Reynoso in a 12–9 win.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On April 9, in his first career home game, Pujols hit a two-run home run in his first at bat against Denny Neagle of Colorado.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Through 2015, he was one of three players to hit 20 or more home runs in their rookie year before July, along with Wally Berger (1930) and Joc Pederson (2015).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] At midseason, Pujols became the first Cardinals rookie since Luis Arroyo in 1955 to make the All-Star Game.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished the season batting .329 (sixth in the league) with 194 hits (fifth in the league), 47 doubles (fifth in the league), 37 home runs, and 112 runs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His 37 home runs led the Cardinals, topping Jim Edmonds' 30 and McGwire's 29.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was named the National League (NL) Silver Slugger Award winner for the third base position, and he finished fourth in NL Most Valuable Player (MVP) voting, behind Barry Bonds, Sammy Sosa and Luis Gonzalez.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was unanimously named the NL Rookie of the Year after setting an NL rookie record with 130 RBI's (fifth in the league) and becoming the fourth MLB rookie to hit .300 with 30 home runs, 100 runs, and 100 RBI's.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals finished the 2001 season with a 93–69 record and advanced to the playoffs as the National League wild card team.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The team advanced to the NL Division Series (NLDS).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 on October 10, Pujols hit a game-winning two-run home run against Diamondbacks pitcher Randy Johnson in a 4–1 victory.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals, however, were eliminated in five games, and Pujols had just two hits in 18 at-bats.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After playing several positions in 2001, Pujols spent most of 2002 in left field.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He began the season batting cleanup but was moved in May to the third spot in the lineup, where he remained for the rest of his Cardinals career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 30th home run and 100th RBI of the season in a 5–4 loss to the Cincinnati Reds in August, making him the sixth Cardinal to have back-to-back 30-home-run seasons and the second Cardinal (the other was Ray Jablonski) to start his career with back-to-back 100-RBI seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The following month, Pujols hit a game-winning two-run single against Pete Munro in a 9–3 victory over the Houston Astros that gave the Cardinals the NL Central title.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the year batting .314 (seventh in the NL) with 185 hits (tied for fourth in the NL), 40 doubles (eighth in the NL), 34 home runs (10th in the NL), 118 runs scored (second in the NL to Sosa's 122), and 127 RBI's (second in the NL).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He became the first player in major league history to hit over .300 with at least 30 home runs, 100 runs scored, and 100 RBI in his first two seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished second in MVP voting to Bonds, becoming the first Cardinal since Stan Musial to finish in the top four in MVP voting for consecutive seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' contributions helped the Cardinals finish third in home runs and second in batting average and RBI; the Cardinals' pitching staff also finished fourth in ERA.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals again reached the playoffs, and Pujols had three hits and three RBI in a three-game sweep of the Diamondbacks in the 2002 NLDS.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The team advanced to the 2002 NL Championship Series (NLCS), but lost in five games to the San Francisco Giants.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had five hits, one home run and two RBI in the series.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Five Cardinals were named to the All-Star Game in 2003 while Pujols led the NL in votes.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] It was the first of eight straight seasons that Pujols would reach the All-Star Game.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] From July 12 to August 16, Pujols had a 30-game hitting streak, tied for the second-longest in Cardinals' history with Musial and behind only Rogers Hornsby's 33-game streak.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 20, Pujols hit his 100th career home run, a game-winner in a 10–7 victory over the Dodgers.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He became the fourth major leaguer to hit his 100th home run in his third season, along with Ralph Kiner, Eddie Mathews and Joe DiMaggio.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 114th home run on September 20 in a game against the Astros, which tied him with Kiner for the most home runs by a player in his first three seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 157 games, Pujols hit 43 home runs (fourth in the league, behind Jim Thome, Richie Sexson and Bonds) and had 124 RBI's (tied with Sexson for fourth and behind Preston Wilson, Gary Sheffield and Thome).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He became the youngest player since Tommy Davis in 1962 to win the NL batting title after batting .359, and he led the league in runs (137), hits (212), and doubles (51).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols joined Rogers Hornsby as the only players in the Cardinals' history to record more than 40 homers and 200 hits in the same season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Though his stellar play had Cardinals' fans chanting "M-V-P!" during home games as early as June, Pujols again finished second to Bonds in MVP voting.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He won his second Silver Slugger Award and first *Sporting News* Player of the Year Award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' contributions helped the Cardinals rank second in batting average and third in home runs in the NL; however, the pitching staff posted a 4.60 ERA, which was below the league average, and the Cardinals missed the playoffs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After receiving many awards in his first three seasons, Pujols was rewarded monetarily for his accomplishments on February 20, 2004, when he signed a seven-year, $100 million contract extension with a $16 million club option for 2011 with no-trade provisions.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was moved to first base in 2004 after the Cardinals traded Tino Martinez in the offseason.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 16, he hit a walk-off home run against Reds pitcher Mike Matthews in the 10th inning of a 4–3 victory.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' highlights later in the season included a July game in which he hit five RBI and three home runs in a thrilling win over the rival Chicago Cubs, and another in which he broke up a no-hitter by Giants pitcher Dustin Hermanson.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] During a September game against the Rockies, he earned his 500th RBI, joining Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams as the only players to have 500 RBI in their first four seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He also led the league with 133 runs scored.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On defense, he tied for the league lead in errors by a first baseman, with 14.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished third in MVP voting (behind Bonds and Beltré), joining Musial as the only Cardinals to finish in the top five in voting for at least four years in a row.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He won the Silver Slugger Award at first base, the third position he won the award at.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols, along with teammates Edmonds and Rolen, earned the nickname "MV3" for their phenomenal seasons; Pujols led the three in home runs and batting average.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the NL Central, aided by pitcher Chris Carpenter, who won 15 games and had a 3.46 ERA his first season with the team en route to winning the National League Comeback Player of the Year Award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 4 of the NLDS against the Dodgers, Pujols hit a three-run home run against Wilson Álvarez and had four RBI as the Cardinals won, 6–2, and took the series three games to one.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 6 of the NLCS, Pujols had three hits, scored three runs (including the winning run), and hit a two-run home run off Munro in a 12-inning, 6–4 victory.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the series in seven games, advancing to the World Series for the first time since 1987.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was named the NLCS MVP after batting .500 with four home runs and nine RBI.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was one of three Cardinals batters hit over .250 in the series against the Boston Red Sox, batting .333 as the Cardinals were swept by Boston in four games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] By 2005, many baseball fans thought that Pujols was the best Cardinal since Musial.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols picked up his 100th RBI of the season on August 31, joining Williams, DiMaggio and Al Simmons as the only players with 100 RBI in their first five seasons.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 200th career home run in a game against the Reds on September 30, making him the third-youngest major league player to reach that milestone (behind Mel Ott and Eddie Mathews) and the second-fastest to reach it (behind Kiner).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the first time in his career, he won the NL MVP award as Bonds was limited to 14 games due to an injury.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols returned to the playoffs as the Cardinals won the NL Central for the second year in a row.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had five hits in nine at-bats with four runs scored and two RBI in the NLDS as the Cardinals swept the Padres.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 5 of the NLCS against the Astros, with the Cardinals trailing by two runs and only one out from elimination in the ninth inning, Pujols hit a game-winning three-run home run against Brad Lidge that landed on the train tracks in the back of Minute Maid Park.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] *MLB.com* writer Matthew Leach later called it "one of the most famous playoff home runs in recent years." Nevertheless, the Cardinals were eliminated in Game 6 by the Astros.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols batted .304 with two home runs and six RBI in the series.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Over two games in April 2006, Pujols hit home runs in four consecutive plate appearances, making him the 20th player to accomplish the feat.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols maintained after the game that he was more concerned with winning than the numbers: "I don't look at numbers," he said.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] I didn't know anything about [the record] until you guys brought it up.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] I don't get locked in on anything like that.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] I get locked in on seeing the ball and helping my team out to win and hopefully doing some damage out there." Pujols had three hits and four RBI, including his 1,000th career hit (a home run against Jerome Williams), as the Cardinals defeated the Cubs 9–3 on April 21, 2006.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 4, he was placed on the disabled list (DL) for the first time in his career with a strained right oblique that kept him out for three weeks.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 22, Pujols hit a three-run home run and a grand slam against John Maine in an 8–7 loss to the Mets.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 28, with the Cardinals trailing the Padres 2–1 in the eighth inning, he hit a three-run home run against Cla Meredith, helping the Cardinals win 4–2 and end a seven-game losing streak.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with a .331 average (third to Freddy Sanchez's .344 and Cabrera's .339), 177 hits, 33 doubles, 49 home runs (second to Ryan Howard's 58), 137 RBI (second to Howard, 149) and 119 runs scored (tied with Matt Holliday, Hanley Ramírez, and Alfonso Soriano for fifth).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Of his 49 home runs, 20 produced a game-winning RBI, breaking Willie Mays' single-season record set in 1962.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished second to Howard in MVP voting and won the NL Gold Glove Award for first base.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He won his first of four consecutive Fielding Bible Awards for the first base position.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Led by Pujols and Carpenter, the Cardinals won the NL Central and reached the playoffs for the third year in a row.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 1 of the NLDS against the Padres, he hit a game-winning two-run home run against Jake Peavy as the Cardinals won 5–1.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had a game-winning RBI against David Wells and had three hits in Game 2 as the Cardinals won 2–0.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .333 with a home run and an RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Padres in four games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLCS against the Mets, Pujols scored three runs as the Cardinals won 9–6.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .318 with one home run and one RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Mets in seven games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 1 of the World Series against the Detroit Tigers, he hit a two-run home run against Justin Verlander as the Cardinals won 7–2.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 5, he made a sprawling, flip-from-his-back play to rob Plácido Polanco of a hit as the Cardinals clinched the series, giving Pujols his first career World Series ring.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Near the beginning of the 2007 season in an April 22 game against the Cubs, Pujols hit a game-winning three-run home run against Ryan Dempster in the 10th inning of a 12–9 victory, tying Ken Boyer for second all-time on the Cardinals' home run list with his 255th.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with 185 hits, 38 doubles and 103 RBI (a career-low).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was among the league leaders in batting average (.327, sixth) and home runs (32, tied for tenth).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He scored 99 runs, ending his streak of seasons with at least 30 home runs, a .300 average, 100 runs scored and 100 RBI, at six.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He grounded into a major-league-leading 27 double plays.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished ninth in MVP voting, the first year he had finished outside the top five.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began 2008 by reaching base in 42 straight games, the longest streak to open a season since 1999.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 11, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list with a strained left calf muscle.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 300th home run against Bob Howry on July 4 in a 2–1 loss to the Cubs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He said after the game that to him it was "just another homer that goes out of the park.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He regretted that the milestone came in a loss, saying, "I wish it would have come with a great win.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He grounded into a National League-leading 27 double plays.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols won his second NL MVP Award, and he won the Silver Slugger Award for the fourth time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was named *The Sporting News* Player of the Year for the second time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For his work off the field, he was named the 2008 winner of the Roberto Clemente Award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He considered having Tommy John surgery after the season but underwent nerve transposition surgery on his right elbow instead to ease discomfort.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On April 25, 2009, Pujols picked up his 1,000th career RBI with a 441-foot grand slam against David Patton in an 8–2 victory over the Cubs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "I hit that ball as good as I can hit a ball," he said after the game.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 3, he hit his 10th career grand slam against Weathers in a 7–4 victory over the Reds, breaking Musial's record for most grand slams by a Cardinal.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The grand slam was also his 350th career home run, making him the third-fastest player to reach the milestone, behind Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He received the highest number of votes in NL history for the All-Star Game that year.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had four hits, scored three runs, and knocked in five RBI on August 4, including a grand slam against Sean Green that tied the NL record for most grand slams in a season (five), in a 10-inning, 12–7 victory over the Mets.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 160 games, Pujols batted .327 (third, behind Ramírez's .342 and Pablo Sandoval's .330) with 186 hits (sixth), 45 doubles (second to Miguel Tejada's 46), 47 home runs (first), 135 RBI (third behind Fielder and Howard's 141) and 124 runs scored (first).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was unanimously named the NL MVP for the third time, tying Musial as the Cardinals' leader in that category.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the fifth time in his career, he won the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He won the *Sporting News* MLB Player of the Year award for the second consecutive year, joining Williams and Joe Morgan as the only players to win it in back-to-back years.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the fourth year in a row, he won the Fielding Bible Award for first base.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Aided by the mid-season acquisition of Matt Holliday (who replaced Ryan Ludwick as the cleanup hitter) and the emergence of Adam Wainwright (who led the NL in wins), the Cardinals returned to the playoffs after a two-year hiatus.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In the NLDS against the Dodgers, Pujols batted .300 with one RBI as the Cardinals were swept in three games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Following the postseason, Pujols had surgery to remove five bone spurs from his right elbow.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals called the surgery a "success", and Dr.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] James Andrews decided that Pujols did not need Tommy John surgery.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For April 2010, Pujols earned his first Pepsi Clutch Performer of the Month Award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .348, 1.270 OPS, three home runs and 14 RBI with runners on base.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Further, in situations with his team leading by one run, tied, or having the potential tying run on base, at bat, or on deck after the seventh inning ("late-and-close"), he batted .583 (7-for-12) with a home run, two doubles, three RBI and five runs scored.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 29, in an 8–0 victory over the Diamondbacks, Pujols hit five RBI and hit two home runs against Dontrelle Willis for his 37th career multi-homer game, which tied Musial's franchise record for multi-homer games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "It's pretty special," he said of tying Musial.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "I'm blessed to have the opportunity to be compared sometimes with him." On August 26, he hit his 400th career home run against Jordan Zimmermann in a 13-inning, 11–10 loss to the Nationals.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He became the third-youngest player to reach the milestone – behind Griffey Jr. and Rodriguez – and he became the fourth-quickest player by at bats to reach the milestone (behind McGwire, Babe Ruth, Harmon Killebrew, and Thome).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 11, in a 12-inning 6–3 loss to Atlanta, Pujols had three RBI and reached 100 RBI for the 10th consecutive year with a two-run double against Tommy Hanson.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Only Al Simmons has a longer streak of 100 RBI seasons at the beginning of a career, with 11.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols joined Jimmie Foxx, Lou Gehrig, and Rodriguez in having 10 consecutive seasons of 100 or more RBI at any time in their career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Foxx and Rodriguez are the only two players besides Pujols to have 10 consecutive years of 30 home runs and 100 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The next day, in a 7–3 victory over the Braves, he passed Musial to be the all-time Cardinals' leader in multi-home run games when he hit two home runs against Tim Hudson for the 38th time in a game.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 159 games, Pujols batted .312 (sixth) with 183 hits (fifth) and 39 doubles (tied for eighth with Marlon Byrd); he led the league in runs scored (115), home runs (42) and RBI (118).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He won his second Gold Glove Award for first base, and he won the NL First Base Silver Slugger Award for the sixth time.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He finished second in the NL MVP voting to Joey Votto, who said he was "shocked" that Pujols only got one first-place vote.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols and the Cardinals set a deadline for the start of 2011 spring training for contract extension negotiations but failed to reach an agreement.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After Pujols struggled in his first 30 games of the season in batting .231, he batted .316 with 30 home runs in his final 117 games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Against the Cubs, he hit consecutive extra-inning walk-off home runs on June 4 and 5 for the first time since Albert Belle in 1995.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Carpenter noted after the game that Pujols' slump earlier in the year was over: "He continues to do great things, there's no doubt about it," he said.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "The things that he's done the last few days have been just like the old Albert." On June 19 against the Royals, Wilson Betemit collided with Pujols, inducing a small fracture his left wrist and keeping him inactive until July 5.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 30, in a 9–2 victory over the Cubs, he got his 2,000th career hit against Carlos Mármol, becoming the fifth Cardinal to reach 2,000 hits and 12th-fastest major leaguer by games to reach the milestone.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In the Cardinals' final game of the season, against the Astros on September 28, he had the game-winning RBI against Brett Myers in the 8–0 victory, helping the Cardinals overcome a 10.5-game deficit to Atlanta to win the Wild Card.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with 173 hits (tied for ninth with Aramis Ramírez), 29 doubles (a career-low), and 105 runs scored (tied for third with Justin Upton behind Ryan Braun's 109 and Matt Kemp's 115).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLDS against the Phillies on October 2, Pujols had a game-winning RBI single against Cliff Lee in the 5–4 victory.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .350 with one RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Phillies in five games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLCS against the Brewers, he had four hits, three runs scored, one home run and five RBI, in a 12–3 victory.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .478 with two home runs and nine RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Brewers in six games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On October 22, in Game 3 of the World Series, Pujols had five hits, three home runs, four runs scored and six RBI in a 16–7 victory over the Rangers.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had one hit and no RBI the other six games of the series but became a World Series champion for the second time as the Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After the season, he became a free agent for the first time in his career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Three teams were reported to be interested in Pujols during the 2011 offseason: the Cardinals, the Miami Marlins, and the Los Angeles Angels.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals offered Pujols a 10-year, $210 million deal (with $30 million deferred), but Pujols rejected it.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His wife, Deidre, explained on a radio talk show that they were "insulted" and "confused" that the Cardinals had initially offered Pujols a five-year deal.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Marlins reportedly offered Pujols a 10-year contract too, but on December 8, he signed a 10-year deal with the Angels worth around $254 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols did not perform very well to begin the 2012 season, batting .217 with no home runs and four RBI in the month of April.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Soon after the Angels called up top prospect Mike Trout and fired hitting coach Mickey Hatcher, Pujols' numbers began to rise, as he batted .323 with 13 home runs from May 15 through the All-Star Break.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 31, he hit two home runs against Derek Holland in a 6–2 victory over the Rangers.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After the game, Holland observed that Pujols had "definitely turned it around, no doubt about it...
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had a slow start, but he's picked it up.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He's a great hitter...." On August 14, Pujols had four RBIs, including a game-winning three-run home run against Ubaldo Jiménez in a 9–6 victory over the Cleveland Indians.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 2012, Pujols batted .285 (at the time, a career low) in 153 games with 173 hits, 50 doubles (second to Alex Gordon's 51), 30 home runs, 105 RBIs (7th in AL), and 85 runs scored.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 2013, Pujols had by far the worst season of his career to date, failing to play at least 100 games in a season for the first time.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols also posted career worsts in hits, runs scored, doubles, home runs, RBI, walks, batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and OPS.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Overall in 99 games, Pujols batted .258 with 101 hits, 19 doubles, 17 home runs, 64 RBI, and 49 runs scored.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 19, 2013, Pujols was ruled out for the remainder of the 2013 season after suffering a foot injury.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Louis WGNU radio show, former Cardinals player Jack Clark accused Pujols of having used performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Clark served as the Cardinals' hitting coach during the early part of Pujols' tenure in St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On the morning of August 9, Pujols issued a statement adamantly denying that he had ever taken PEDs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He denounced Clark's allegations as "irresponsible and reckless," and threatened to sue Clark and WGNU over the allegations.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Partly due to legal threats from Pujols, InsideSTL Enterprises, which owns WGNU's weekday airtime under a time brokerage agreement, cut ties with Clark.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On October 4, 2013, Pujols filed a defamation lawsuit against Clark.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In response, Clark challenged Pujols, proposing that they both take polygraph tests to resolve who is telling the truth.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] However, on February 10, 2014, Clark apologized and retracted his accusations against Pujols, saying he had "no knowledge whatsoever" that Pujols ever used PEDs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "During a heated discussion on air, I misspoke," Clark said.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On April 22, 2014, Pujols hit his 499th and 500th home runs off the Washington Nationals' Taylor Jordan at Nationals Park, where he had hit his 400th career home run in the 2010 season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols became the 26th player ever to reach the 500-home-run mark, the third-youngest to reach it, and the only player to hit Nos.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 10, he played in MLB's longest game of the year, and the longest in the history of Angel Stadium, ending the 19-inning, 6-hours-and-31-minute contest against the Red Sox with a solo home run for a 5–4 final score.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] It was his first walk-off home run as an Angel and first since June 2011.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 6, against the Minnesota Twins, Pujols collected his 2,500th career hit, a two-run go-ahead double off of Jared Burton in the 9th inning.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He also passed the 1,500-run mark in the same game.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In the process, he became the fifth player in major league history with 2,500 hits and 500 home runs while maintaining a .310 lifetime batting average, after Babe Ruth, Jimmie Foxx, Ted Williams and Manny Ramirez.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2014 season, Pujols batted .272 and grounded into an American League-leading 28 double plays.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 3rd-highest salary in the AL, at $23 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After the 2014 season, Pujols traveled to Japan to join a team of MLB All-Stars playing against the All-Stars of Nippon Professional Baseball in the Japan All-Star Series.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Before the 2015 season, Pujols enjoyed his first offseason in his time with the Angels in which he was both free of injury or recuperation from injury.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] However, his offensive production lagged behind his career levels the first month of the season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] By the end of April, Pujols was batting .208 with three home runs and nine RBI in 86 plate appearances.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The next month, Pujols' offensive production had started to come around.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Between May 28 and June 22, he batted .356 with 15 homers, 30 RBI, and a 1.326 OPS.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] At this time, he was leading the American League in home runs with 23.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After batting .303/.395/.737 with 13 home runs in June 2015, Pujols was named AL Player of the Month for the first time and seventh overall monthly award.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His home run total led the major leagues and 73 total bases tied Manny Machado for first in the AL.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Remarkably, his batting average on balls in play was .218, significantly lower than the league average of about .300.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Selected to the All Star Game, Pujols was announced as a reserve for the American League.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Due to an injury just days earlier with Tigers slugger Miguel Cabrera, Pujols instead started at first base.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] It was his 10th overall selection to the midsummer classic, and first as a member of the Angels.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 22, Pujols hit his 556th career home run to pass Ramírez for sole possession of 14th place on the all-time career home run leaderboard.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In the last game of the season, on October 4, Pujols hit his 40th home run, the seventh time he had done so in a season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Among active MLB players, he trailed only Alex Rodriguez, with eight.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] With Trout also hitting 40 home runs, the 2015 Angels became just the 31st team in MLB history with multiple players to hit 40+ home runs in a season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2015 season, he batted .244/.307/.480, and he had the lowest batting average on balls in play (.217) of all major league players.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 3rd-highest salary in the AL, at $24 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On April 30, 2016, Pujols became the 85th player to make 10,000 career plate appearances.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 2, Pujols became the 20th player all-time to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 17, Pujols joined Barry Bonds as the only other player to be intentionally walked over 300 times.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Playing the Toronto Blue Jays on August 25, he reached 100 RBI for the 13th time in his career, the fifth player to do so.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] While playing Cincinnati on August 29, Pujols hit his 26th home run and 103rd RBI of the season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The home run tied him with Frank Robinson for ninth place on the all-time home run list at 586, and allowed him to become the seventh player all-time with 1,200 career extra base hits, and the 21st to reach 1,800 RBI.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 16, Pujols became the 16th player all-time to reach 600 career doubles.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He tied for 2nd in the AL in double plays grounded into, with 24.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 6th-highest salary in the league, at $25 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 3, 2017, Pujols became the ninth player in Major League history to hit at least 600 home runs, when he hit a grand slam off of Ervin Santana of the Minnesota Twins.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was the fourth-youngest player to achieve the feat (behind Alex Rodriguez, Babe Ruth and Hank Aaron), and the first to hit a grand slam for his 600th home run.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2017 season, Pujols played in 149 games and had 593 at bats, but set career-lows in batting average (.241), on base percentage (.286), slugging percentage (.386), doubles (17), and walks (37), while leading the majors by grounding into 26 double plays.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players, at 21.8 feet/second.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 6th-highest salary in the AL, at $26 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 4, 2018, Pujols recorded his 3,000th major league hit, against Mike Leake of the Seattle Mariners.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 12, Pujols hit his 630th career home run, moving into a tie with Ken Griffey Jr. for sixth place all-time for that category.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The next day, Pujols was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to left knee inflammation.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He hit a single on August 10 for his 1,000th hit as an Angel, becoming the ninth player to record 1,000 hits in both the American League and National League.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had surgery on his left knee in August, ending his season, and on his right elbow to remove a bone spur in September.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 2018, he batted .245/.289/.411 with 19 home runs and 64 RBIs (matching the lowest season total of his career).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players for the second consecutive year, at 22.2 feet/second.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was the sixth-oldest player in the American League.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 5th-highest salary in the AL, at $27 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 9, 2019, Pujols became the fourth player in major league history to record 2,000 RBIs, hitting a solo home run against the Detroit Tigers at Comerica Park.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] A Tigers fan caught the 2,000 RBI ball but refused to turn it over to MLB officials, saying that he wanted to sleep on it before making a decision.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In response, MLB refused to authenticate the ball.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The fan, Ely Hydes, eventually decided that he wanted to return the ball to Pujols, who in turn refused, stating that the fan should either keep the ball or donate it to the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 200th home run as an Angel on June 13, becoming only the sixth player to hit 200 home runs with two different teams.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had the lowest line drive percentage of all major league hitters (15.3%), and the 16.7% of balls he hit to the opposite field were the lowest in baseball.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the second-slowest sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.5 feet/second.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was the third-oldest player in the American League, behind Ichiro Suzuki (who retired in March) and Fernando Rodney.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 4th-highest salary in the AL, at $28 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] At the beginning of the 2020 season, Pujols (at the age of 40) was the oldest player in the major leagues.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 24, Pujols passed Rodriguez to reach second on the all-time RBIs list with a single against the Astros.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] With his 2,087th RBI, he trailed only Hank Aaron's 2,297.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] (Babe Ruth has 2,214 RBIs as recognized by Baseball Reference, but only 1,989 on the official MLB list; MLB does not count pre-1920 RBIs because it was not yet an official statistic.) On September 18, Pujols hit his 661st career home run to pass Willie Mays for fifth place all-time.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.0 feet/second.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 7th-highest salary in the league, at $29 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began the 2021 season with the Angels.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 6, 2021, the Angels designated Pujols for assignment.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Through 24 games, Pujols was hitting .198/.250/.372 with five home runs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 13, Pujols cleared waivers and became a free agent.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In nine-plus seasons with the Angels, Pujols hit .256 with 222 homers and 783 runs batted in.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] During his time with the Angels, the team won the AL West once (in 2014) and won no postseason games.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In 2016, sportswriter Joe Posnanski of NBC Sports described Pujols as "a cautionary tale against big contracts" and "an overpaid designated hitter in the middle of the lineup for a going-nowhere Los Angeles Angels team".
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 17, 2021, Pujols agreed to a one-year major league deal with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He made his Dodgers debut that night as the starting first baseman against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] With his longtime number 5 having been assigned to Corey Seager, Pujols chose the number 55; both as nods to his two former teams, as well as the Bible.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] "If you know the Bible," Pujols explained, "it's the number of grace.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] So I feel 5-5, double grace." On May 20, Pujols hit his first home run as a Dodger, a two-run homer off Merrill Kelly of the Diamondbacks.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In October, Scott Miller of *The New York Times* asserted that Pujols had "flourished beyond expectations, scorching lefties for a .306 batting average".
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Overall, in 2021 he appeared in 85 games for the Dodgers and hit .254 with a .299 on base percentage, 12 homers, and 38 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] For the second season in a row, he had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.4 feet/second.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His line drive percentage of 15.4% was the lowest in the major leagues, and his 16.7% of balls hit to the opposite field was the lowest in the majors.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was the oldest player in the league for the second season in a row, and had the fifth-highest salary at $30 million.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In his first postseason appearance since 2014, he appeared in nine games for the Dodgers, with five hits in 18 at bats for a batting average of .278.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols subsequently announced that he would play in the Dominican Professional Baseball League (LIDOM) in the offseason, for Leones del Escogido.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On March 28, 2022, Pujols signed a one-year contract to return to the St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Louis Cardinals and announced that 2022 would be his final season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He said, "There were a lot of teams interested.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] It took 12 hours, maybe even less, to get a deal done once we received a call from the Cardinals," adding: "We have the best fans in baseball.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] It feels like I never left." He was the oldest player in the major leagues for the third season in a row.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On May 15, Pujols made his pitching debut, the oldest player to do so since 1929.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In a 15–6 blowout win against the San Francisco Giants, he gave up two home runs and four earned runs in the ninth inning.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 4 against the Chicago Cubs, he became the 10th major league player to play 3,000 games, appearing as an injury replacement for Corey Dickerson.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On June 7 against the Tampa Bay Rays, Pujols singled for his 3,320th career hit, passing Paul Molitor for tenth all-time in hits.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On July 10, after the Philadelphia Phillies had shut out the Cardinals in three straight games, Pujols made a rare start against a right-handed pitcher, and his three hits, including a home run, helped spark a 4–3 win.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The home run was Pujols' 1,377th extra-base hit, tying him for third all-time with Stan Musial.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was chosen to be on the National League team for the All-Star Game by MLB Commissioner Rob Manfred as a "legacy" selection to honor his career achievements.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was also selected to participate in the Home Run Derby, where he advanced to the second round and fell one home run short of eventual winner Juan Soto.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 20, he passed Musial for second place all-time in total bases, trailing only Hank Aaron.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols became the first player to produce four hits and two homers in a single game at age 42 or older and was named the National League Player of the Week (alongside teammate Paul Goldschmidt) after hitting .615 with three home runs and seven RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On August 29, Pujols hit a third-inning home run off of Ross Detwiler, the 450th unique pitcher to surrender a home run to Pujols, breaking another MLB record.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 10 and 11, Pujols hit his 696th and 697th home runs, at PNC Park against the Pittsburgh Pirates, to move into fourth place on the all-time list.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 14, he became the second player in MLB history to officially compile 2,200 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols on hitting his 700th home run in Los Angeles.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On September 23, Pujols became the fourth player to hit 700 career home runs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] His 699th and 700th home runs came during consecutive at-bats during an 11–0 victory for the Cardinals at Dodger Stadium.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] 699 off Andrew Heaney, his 200th home run off a left-handed pitcher; and his 700th off Phil Bickford, his 500th home run off a right-handed pitcher.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] 702 in his last career home game, mirroring the home run he hit in his St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] 703, which gave him undisputed possession of second place on the all-time RBI list, surpassing Babe Ruth's unofficial total.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished his regular-season career first in double plays grounded into (426), third in sacrifice flies (123), fifth in games played (3,080) and doubles (686), and sixth in at bats (11,421).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After the season was finished, Pujols was named National League Comeback Player of the Year.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the National League Central division, earning a berth in the postseason and enabling Pujols' 10th and final postseason appearance.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He went 2-for-8 in the National League Wild Card Series against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 on October 8, he singled in his last two at-bats.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Phillies won the game, eliminating the Cardinals and bringing Pujols' playing career to an end.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On November 1, it was announced that Pujols had signed retirement papers with the Cardinals.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On February 23, 2023, the Angels hired Pujols as a special assistant as part of a 10–year personal services contract.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Since retiring, Pujols has also been an analyst on MLB Network.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In June 2023, Pujols was named the "official global ambassador" of Baseball United, a professional baseball organization in the Middle East and South Asia.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] He was also reported to have an ownership interest in the league.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] After his playing career, Pujols has also been involved in the managerial side of things, a rarity for all-time greats.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] In February 2024, Pujols was named the manager of the Leones del Escogido.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] The Leones del Escogido won the Serie Final of the 2024–25 season and the 2025 Caribbean Series.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] Ramón Santiago was hired to replace Pujols for the 2025–26 season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p01] On December 28, 2025, the Estrellas Orientales announced that Pujols would be their manager for the 2026–27 season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols' swing was praised for its consistency.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] "It's the same swing every time," former teammate Lance Berkman once said.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] "He has the ability to repeat his swing over and over and over, which leads to him being very consistent," Cardinals' video coordinator Chad Blair said.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Habib described the swing as "quick" and "quiet".
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols used a 32.5-ounce bat against right-handed pitchers, but used a 33-ounce bat against left-handers to avoid trying to pull the ball when he swung.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is second in major league history in runs batted in and total bases behind only Hank Aaron.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] He and Aaron are the only two players to amass 3,000 hits, 700 home runs, and 2,200 RBIs.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Only two other players (Stan Musial and Willie Mays) have surpassed 6,000 total bases.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols hit home runs off of a record 458 different pitchers over the course of his career, and is fourth in career home runs and fifth in doubles.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, Pujols set the major league single-season record for assists by a first baseman with 185.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In an age when seasons of 150+ strikeouts were the norm for sluggers, he never struck out 100 times in a season.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols earned uncommonly high praise from players and coaches throughout his career.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2008, he was named the most feared hitter in baseball in a poll of all 30 MLB managers.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Given his career achievements, Pujols is widely expected to be inducted into the Hall of Fame and potentially a unanimous selection the first year in which he becomes eligible (2028).
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2006, Pujols and the Hanon family opened Pujols 5 Westport Grill, a restaurant located in Westport Plaza of Maryland Heights, Missouri.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] A 10-foot, 1,100-lb. statue of Pujols was dedicated on November 2, 2011, outside the restaurant.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] An anonymous donor commissioned sculptor Harry Weber to create the statue, which belongs to the Pujols Family Foundation.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] After Pujols signed with the Angels, the restaurant was renamed the St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Louis Soccer United, a group looking to bring a Major League Soccer (MLS) franchise to the St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] However, the group's bid for a franchise was unsuccessful, and a USL team (Saint Louis FC) was formed.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Among other activities, the foundation hosts events for people with Down syndrome.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] The foundation gave the Down Syndrome Association of Greater St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Louis the resources to open an office and hire staff.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, the Albert Pujols Wellness Center for Adults with Down Syndrome opened in Chesterfield, Missouri; Pujols was present at the opening on November 18.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] The foundation hosts an annual "All Stars Basketball Game" with down syndrome players at Missouri Baptist University.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols has been a part of several medical missions to the Dominican Republic, by taking supplies as well as supporting doctors and dentists for those in need medical care.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] The Pujols Family Foundation also holds an annual golf tournament to raise money to send dentists to the Dominican Republic.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, Pujols donated money to the Mike Coolbaugh Memorial Tournament, allowing the event to occur after a sponsor backed out.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] On August 28, 2010, Pujols and La Russa attended Glenn Beck's "Restoring Honor" rally in Washington, D.C., after being assured by Beck that the rally was not political.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] During the rally, Pujols was presented with a medal for his off-the-field efforts.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols married Deidre Pujols on January 1, 2000.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] He filed for divorce on April 4, 2022, after 22 years of marriage, citing irreconcilable differences.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is a devout evangelical Christian.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] He became an evangelical Christian on November 13, 1998, influenced in part by Deidre and his grandmother.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] During his first tenure with the Cardinals, Pujols and his family attended West County Community Church, a Southern Baptist church in Wildwood, Missouri.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] On September 2, 2023, Pujols married Nicole Fernandez, the daughter of former President of the Dominican Republic, Leonel Fernández.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] The two had been dating since September 2022, shortly before Pujols’ playing career ended.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] During his playing days, even with the Angels and Dodgers, Pujols lived in St.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] He owned a home in Irvine, California, but put it up for sale in 2016.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is a supporter of people with Down syndrome, a condition his daughter Isabella was born with.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] In 2007, Pujols became a U.S. citizen, scoring a perfect 100 on his citizenship test.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is close friends with third baseman Plácido Polanco, a former teammate with the Cardinals.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Polanco has called Pujols his "closest friend in baseball", and Pujols is the godfather to Polanco's son, Ishmael.
[src:charley-jones/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is also friends with Robinson Canó, who selected Pujols' Angels teammate Mark Trumbo for the 2012 Home Run Derby after being asked to by Pujols.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] Jones played for several teams; the Keokuk Westerns, Hartford Dark Blues, Cincinnati Reds (NL), Chicago White Stockings, Boston Red Caps, Cincinnati Red Stockings (AA), New York Metropolitans, and Kansas City Cowboys.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] A popular but controversial player, despite his hitting ability he never played for a league champion.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] On June 10, 1880, Jones became the first big leaguer to hit two homers in the same inning.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] Both home runs came off Buffalo Bisons' pitcher Tom Poorman in the eighth inning of a 19–3 rout.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] Jones best period was from 1883 to 1885, when he hit 22 home runs, had 186 RBI, and batted .310.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] Through the first nine seasons of the major leagues' existence, Jones held the career record for home runs, despite missing two of those seasons (1881–82) as a result of being blackballed from the sport.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] By 1889, he was just tenth, and by 1890 he was no longer among the top ten.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] After his playing career concluded, Jones spent two seasons as an umpire.
[src:charley-jones/charley-jones] He umpired 121 games in the Players' League in 1890, and 76 games in the American Association in 1891.
